{"title_page": "Penelope Milford", "text_new": "{{short description|American stage and screen actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Penelope Milford\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1948|03|23}}\n| birth_place = [[St. Louis, Missouri]], U.S.\n| yearsactive = 1968\u2013present\n| occupation  = Actress\n| family      = [[Kim Milford]] (brother)\n}}\n'''Penelope Milford''' (born March 23, 1948) is an [[Americans|American]] stage and screen actress. She is best known for her role as Vi Munson in ''[[Coming Home (1978 film)|Coming Home]]'' (1978) for which she was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]]. She also originated the role of Jenny Anderson in the Broadway musical ''[[Shenandoah (musical)|Shenandoah]]'', for which she was nominated for a [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Featured Actress in a Musical|Drama Desk Award]] in 1975.\n\n==Early life and education==\n'''Penelope Dale Milford''' was born March 23, 1948 in St. Louis, Missouri and grew up in Illinois. She was the daughter of Richard George Milford and Ann Marie (Felt) Milford. She graduated from [[New Trier High School]] in Winnetka, Illinois, an affluent suburb of Chicago. Her younger brother, [[Kim Milford]], was an actor and musician until his death from heart failure at age 37.<ref>http://saugerties.ulsterpublishing.com/view/full_story/11405299/article-11405299</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1499&dat=19790401&id=0VoaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=oCkEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5506,1119084|title=The Milwaukee Journal - Google News Archive Search|work=google.com|accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Theatre===\nIn 1972 Milford joined the Broadway cast of the play ''Lenny'', about the life of actor [[Lenny Bruce]]. In 1974, she was cast as Jenny Anderson in the musical ''[[Shenandoah (musical)|Shenandoah]]'', based on the 1965 film [[Shenandoah (film)|of the same name]]. Shenandoah opened on Broadway on January 7, 1975 and was nominated for the [[Tony Award]] for Best Musical. For her performance, Milford was nominated for the first [[Drama Desk Award]] for [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Featured Actress in a Musical|Best Featured Actress]].\n\n[[Off-Broadway]] in 1971, Milford starred as Judith opposite [[Richard Gere]] in ''Long Time Coming and a Long Time Gone'', a musical about artist [[Richard Fari\u00f1a]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.richardandmimi.com/longtime-musical.html|title=Long Time Coming Musical|work=richardandmimi.com|accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref> Milford has appeared in ''Felix'' (1974), ''Fishing'' (1981) by [[Michael Weller]], and ''Territorial Rites'' (1983). She also performed in a revue show titled ''The Second Hottest Show in Town.''\n\nIn 2013, Milford played the role of Deborah in the [[Harold Pinter]] play ''[[A Kind of Alaska]]'' at the Cocoon Theatre in Rhinebeck, New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hudsonvalleyalmanacweekly.com/2013/03/08/pinter-plays-revived-in-rhinebeck/|title=Pinter plays revived in Rhinebeck|work=Hudson Valley Almanac Weekly|accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Television===\nHer first television appearance was on a 1976 episode of ''[[The Blue Knight (TV series)|The Blue Knight]]''. In 1980, Milford starred in ''Seizure: The Story of Kathy Morris'', as Kathy Morris. Also in 1980 she co-starred in the [[Emmy Award]] winning television movie ''The Oldest Living Graduate'' starring [[Henry Fonda]] and [[Cloris Leachman]]. In 1982 she starred opposite [[Sondra Locke]] in the [[Jackie Cooper]] directed [[Emmy Award]] winning television film ''Rosie: The Rosemary Clooney Story''. In this film she played Betty Clooney, the sister of [[Rosemary Clooney]]. In 1984, Penelope appeared in the [[Golden Globe]] award-winning television movie ''[[The Burning Bed]]'' starring [[Farrah Fawcett]]. In 1985 she guest starred on an episode of ''[[The Hitchhiker (TV series)|The Hitchhiker]]''.\n\n===Film===\nMilford's first film appearance was as an extra on the [[Norman Mailer]] film ''[[Maidstone (film)|Maidstone]]'' (1970). In 1974, she appeared in the movie ''[[Man on a Swing]]''. She next played a fictional actress named Lorna Sinclair in [[Ken Russell]]'s [[Bafta Award|BAFTA]]-nominated 1977 film ''[[Valentino (1977 film)|Valentino]]'', about the life of actor [[Rudolph Valentino]]. In 1978, she was cast as Vi Munson in ''[[Coming Home (1978 film)|Coming Home]]'', and she was nominated for an Academy Award, for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]. In 1980, she appeared in the movie ''The Last Word''. She plays a supporting role in ''[[Take This Job and Shove It (film)|Take This Job and Shove It]]'' and ''[[Endless Love (1981 film)|Endless Love]]''. In 1982, she starred in the horror film ''Blood Link'' and then starred in the 1983 adventure film ''The Golden Seal''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20073254,00.html|title='Coming Home' to Penny Milford Means Climbing Hollywood's Greasiest Poll\u2014the Oscars|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter this time, her film appearances became less frequent, not appearing until the 1989 cult film ''[[Heathers]]''. Her last few films include ''Cold Justice'' (1989), ''Miss Missouri'' (1990), ''[[Normal Life]]'' (1996), ''[[Henry: Portrait of a Serial Killer, Part II]]'' (1996) and ''Night of the Lawyers'' (1997).\n\n==Filmography==\n*''[[Maidstone (film)|Maidstone]]'' (1970) (uncredited)\n*''[[Man on a Swing]]'' (1974) as Evelyn Moore\n*''[[The Blue Knight (TV series)|The Blue Knight]]'' (1 episode, 1976)\n*''[[Valentino (1977 film)|Valentino]]'' (1977) as Lorna Sinclair\n*''[[Coming Home (1978 film)|Coming Home]]'' (1978) as Vi Munson\n*''The Last Word'' (1979) as Denise Travis\n*''Seizure: The Story of Kathy Morris'' (1980) (TV) as Kathy Morris\n*''[[The Oldest Living Graduate]]'' (1980) (TV) as Martha Ann\n*''[[Take This Job and Shove It (film)|Take This Job and Shove It]]'' (1981) as Lenore Meade\n*''[[Endless Love (1981 film)|Endless Love]]'' (1981) as Ingrid Orchester\n*''Rosie: The Rosemary Clooney Story'' (1982) (TV) as Betty Clooney\n*''[[Blood Link]]'' (1982) as Julie Warren\n*''[[The Golden Seal]]'' (1983) as Tania Lee\n*''[[The Burning Bed]]'' (1984) (TV) as Gaby\n*''[[The Hitchhiker (TV series)|The Hitchhiker]]'' as Diane Hampton (1 episode, 1985)\n*''[[Heathers]]'' (1988) as Pauline Fleming\n*''Cold Justice'' (1989) as Eileen\n*''Miss Missouri'' (1990) as Ann\n*''[[Normal Life]]'' (1996) as Adele Anderson\n*''[[Henry: Portrait of a Serial Killer, Part II]]'' (1996) as Woman in Woods\n*''Night of the Lawyers'' (1997) as Anna Carroll\n\n==Personal life==\nMilford lives in Saugerties, New York.{{Cn|date=August 2015}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0587340}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|12275}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Milford, Penelope}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from St. Louis]]\n[[Category:New Trier High School alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Saugerties, New York]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American stage and screen actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Penelope Milford\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1948|03|23}}\n| birth_place = [[St. Louis, Missouri]], U.S.\n| yearsactive = 1968\u2013present\n| occupation  = Actress\n| family      = [[Kim Milford]] (brother)\n}}\n'''Penelope Milford''' (born March 23, 1948) is an [[Americans|American]] stage and screen actress. She is best known for her role as Vi Munson in ''[[Coming Home (1978 film)|Coming Home]]'' (1978) for which she was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]]. She also originated the role of Jenny Anderson in the Broadway musical ''[[Shenandoah (musical)|Shenandoah]]'', for which she was nominated for a [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Featured Actress in a Musical|Drama Desk Award]] in 1975.\n\n==Early life and education==\n'''Penelope Dale Milford''' was born March 23, 1948 in St. Louis, Missouri and grew up in Illinois. She was the daughter of Richard George Milford and Ann Marie (Felt) Milford. She graduated from [[New Trier High School]] in Winnetka, Illinois, an affluent suburb of Chicago. Her younger brother, [[Kim Milford]], was an actor and musician until his death from heart failure at age 37.<ref>http://saugerties.ulsterpublishing.com/view/full_story/11405299/article-11405299</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1499&dat=19790401&id=0VoaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=oCkEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5506,1119084|title=The Milwaukee Journal - Google News Archive Search|work=google.com|accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Theatre===\nIn 1972 Milford joined the Broadway cast of the play ''Lenny'', about the life of actor [[Lenny Bruce]]. In 1974, she was cast as Jenny Anderson in the musical ''[[Shenandoah (musical)|Shenandoah]]'', based on the 1965 film [[Shenandoah (film)|of the same name]]. Shenandoah opened on Broadway on January 7, 1975 and was nominated for the [[Tony Award]] for Best Musical. For her performance, Milford was nominated for the first [[Drama Desk Award]] for [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Featured Actress in a Musical|Best Featured Actress]].\n\n[[Off-Broadway]] in 1971, Milford starred as Judith opposite [[Richard Gere]] in ''Long Time Coming and a Long Time Gone'', a musical about artist [[Richard Fari\u00f1a]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.richardandmimi.com/longtime-musical.html|title=Long Time Coming Musical|work=richardandmimi.com|accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref> Milford has appeared in ''Felix'' (1974), ''Fishing'' (1981) by [[Michael Weller]], and ''Territorial Rites'' (1983). She also performed in a revue show titled ''The Second Hottest Show in Town.''\n\nIn 2013, Milford played the role of Deborah in the [[Harold Pinter]] play ''[[A Kind of Alaska]]'' at the Cocoon Theatre in Rhinebeck, New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hudsonvalleyalmanacweekly.com/2013/03/08/pinter-plays-revived-in-rhinebeck/|title=Pinter plays revived in Rhinebeck|work=Hudson Valley Almanac Weekly|accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Television===\nHer first television appearance was on a 1976 episode of ''[[The Blue Knight (TV series)|The Blue Knight]]''. In 1980, Milford starred in ''Seizure: The Story of Kathy Morris'', as Kathy Morris. Also in 1980 she co-starred in the [[Emmy Award]] winning television movie ''The Oldest Living Graduate'' starring [[Henry Fonda]] and [[Cloris Leachman]]. In 1982 she starred opposite [[Sondra Locke]] in the [[Jackie Cooper]] directed [[Emmy Award]] winning television film ''Rosie: The Rosemary Clooney Story''. In this film she played Betty Clooney, the sister of [[Rosemary Clooney]]. In 1984, Penelope appeared in the [[Golden Globe]] award-winning television movie ''[[The Burning Bed]]'' starring [[Farrah Fawcett]]. In 1985 she guest starred on an episode of ''[[The Hitchhiker (TV series)|The Hitchhiker]]''.\n\n===Film===\nMilford's first film appearance was as an extra on the [[Norman Mailer]] film ''[[Maidstone (film)|Maidstone]]'' (1970). In 1974, she appeared in the movie ''[[Man on a Swing]]''. She next played a fictional actress named Lorna Sinclair in [[Ken Russell]]'s [[Bafta Award|BAFTA]]-nominated 1977 film ''[[Valentino (1977 film)|Valentino]]'', about the life of actor [[Rudolph Valentino]]. In 1978, she was cast as Vi Munson in ''[[Coming Home (1978 film)|Coming Home]]'', and she was nominated for an Academy Award, for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]. In 1980, she appeared in the movie ''The Last Word''. She plays a supporting role in ''[[Take This Job and Shove It (film)|Take This Job and Shove It]]'' and ''[[Endless Love (1981 film)|Endless Love]]''. In 1982, she starred in the horror film ''Blood Link'' and then starred in the 1983 adventure film ''The Golden Seal''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20073254,00.html|title='Coming Home' to Penny Milford Means Climbing Hollywood's Greasiest Poll\u2014the Oscars|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter this time, her film appearances became less frequent, not appering until the 1989 cult film ''[[Heathers]]''. Her last few films include ''Cold Justice'' (1989), ''Miss Missouri'' (1990), ''[[Normal Life]]'' (1996), ''[[Henry: Portrait of a Serial Killer, Part II]]'' (1996) and ''Night of the Lawyers'' (1997).\n\n==Filmography==\n*''[[Maidstone (film)|Maidstone]]'' (1970) (uncredited)\n*''[[Man on a Swing]]'' (1974) as Evelyn Moore\n*''[[The Blue Knight (TV series)|The Blue Knight]]'' (1 episode, 1976)\n*''[[Valentino (1977 film)|Valentino]]'' (1977) as Lorna Sinclair\n*''[[Coming Home (1978 film)|Coming Home]]'' (1978) as Vi Munson\n*''The Last Word'' (1979) as Denise Travis\n*''Seizure: The Story of Kathy Morris'' (1980) (TV) as Kathy Morris\n*''[[The Oldest Living Graduate]]'' (1980) (TV) as Martha Ann\n*''[[Take This Job and Shove It (film)|Take This Job and Shove It]]'' (1981) as Lenore Meade\n*''[[Endless Love (1981 film)|Endless Love]]'' (1981) as Ingrid Orchester\n*''Rosie: The Rosemary Clooney Story'' (1982) (TV) as Betty Clooney\n*''[[Blood Link]]'' (1982) as Julie Warren\n*''[[The Golden Seal]]'' (1983) as Tania Lee\n*''[[The Burning Bed]]'' (1984) (TV) as Gaby\n*''[[The Hitchhiker (TV series)|The Hitchhiker]]'' as Diane Hampton (1 episode, 1985)\n*''[[Heathers]]'' (1988) as Pauline Fleming\n*''Cold Justice'' (1989) as Eileen\n*''Miss Missouri'' (1990) as Ann\n*''[[Normal Life]]'' (1996) as Adele Anderson\n*''[[Henry: Portrait of a Serial Killer, Part II]]'' (1996) as Woman in Woods\n*''Night of the Lawyers'' (1997) as Anna Carroll\n\n==Personal life==\nMilford lives in Saugerties, New York.{{Cn|date=August 2015}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0587340}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|12275}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Milford, Penelope}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from St. Louis]]\n[[Category:New Trier High School alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Saugerties, New York]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "appering->appearing -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Penelope_Milford"}
