zza]]<br>{{flagicon image|Al-Liwaa.svg}} [[Jaysh al-Ahrar]]<br>{{flag|Turkey}}\n| combatant3  = {{flagdeco|ISIL}} [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]\n*Wilayat Idlib\n**{{flagicon image|Flag of Jund al-Aqsa.svg}} [[Jund al-Aqsa]]\n**{{flagicon image|LiwaDawudFlag.jpg}} [[Liwa Dawud]] remnants\n----\n{{flagicon image|AnsaralTawhidFlag.png}} [[Ansar al-Tawhid (Syria)|Ansar al-Tawhid]]<br>{{flagicon image|Guardians Of Religion INFOBOX flag.png}} [[Guardians of Religion Organization]] <small>(Sometimes)</small>\n| combatant4 =\n{{flagdeco|Syrian Opposition}} [[Syrian Liberation Front]]\n*{{flagicon image|Al-Liwaa.svg}} [[Nour al-Din al-Zenki Movement]]\n*{{flagicon image|Flag of Ahrar ash-Sham.svg}} [[Ahrar al-Sham]] \n| commander1  = Unknown\n| commander2  = {{flagicon image|Flag of Hayat Tahrir al-Sham.svg}} [[Abdullah al-Muhaysini]]<br>{{flagicon image|Flag of Hayat Tahrir al-Sham.svg}} Abu Khadija Bilal al-Khuraisat{{KIA}}<br>{{flagicon image|Guardians Of Religion INFOBOX flag.png}} Abu Al-Walid al-Tunisi{{KIA}}\n| commander3  = {{flagdeco|ISIL}} Ali Nejdet Aldiri{{POW}}<br>{{flagdeco|ISIL}} Said al-Hunaiti{{POW}}<br>{{flagdeco|ISIL}} Abu Khattab Kafr-Nabudah{{POW}}\n| commander4  = {{flagicon image|Flag of Ahrar ash-Sham.svg}} Ala Abu Ahmed{{KIA}}\n| units1      = {{flagdeco|Syria}} Government loyalists<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/more-rebel-fighters-assassinated-in-idlib-amid-escalated-tensions/|title=More rebel fighters assassinated in Idlib amid escalated tensions|first=Zen|last=Adra|date=July 29, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Military Intelligence Directorate (Syria)|Military Intelligence Directorate]]\n**Female unit\n| units2      = [[Syrian Salvation Government]]\n*Police forces\n| units3      = Unknown \n| units4      = Unknown\n| strength1   = \n| strength2   = \n| casualties1 = \n| casualties2 = \n| casualties3 = \n| notes       = \n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Syrian Civil War}}\n}}\nThe '''Insurgency in Idlib''' is an ongoing insurgency in rebel-held areas in the [[Idlib Governorate]] between multiple factions ranging from supporters of the [[Syrian government]] to rival opposition elements to supporters and members of the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2018/07/islamic-state-targets-rival-jihadists-and-islamists-in-northern-syria.php|title=Islamic State targets rival jihadists and Islamists in northern Syria &#124; FDD's Long War Journal|date=July 15, 2018|website=longwarjournal.org}}</ref> The insurgency is marked by assassinations, bombings as well as light armed confrontations with small arms and raids.\n\n==Timeline==\n===2015===\nIn July 2015, the [[Islamic Front (Syria)|Islamic Front]]'s [[Twitter]] account posted that the group had clashed with an ISIL cell in Idlib.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pbs.twimg.com/media/CKq50Y9WwAAAolK.jpg|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910063013/https://pbs.twimg.com/media/CKq50Y9WwAAAolK.jpg|archivedate=2019-09-10|title=Wayback Machine|date=September 10, 2019|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nOn 31 March 2016, the [[Army of Conquest]] claimed to have captured members of a cell belonging to [[Jaysh al-Thuwar]], an Arab component of the [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] in Idlib that was  reportedly conducting assassinations and kidnappings in the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://orient-news.net/en/news_show/107664/0/news_images/16_3/banners/en/cat_show/50/tamplate/Default/LA/css/all-stylesheets.css|title=Jaysh al-Fatth captures a Jaysh al-Thuwar cell|website=Orient-news.net}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 June 2016, the Army of Conquest's police division published a statement saying that the group's police arrested members of a cell that were helping to smuggle members of ISIL from [[Turkey]] into Idlib.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pbs.twimg.com/media/Clk_lDOWAAEB8uU.jpg|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910064101/https://pbs.twimg.com/media/Clk_lDOWAAEB8uU.jpg|archivedate=2019-09-10|title=Wayback Machine|date=September 10, 2019|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 August 2016, the Army of Conquest coalition released a statement saying the coalition's security forces dismantled an ISIL cell in Idlib after 20 days of surveillance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pbs.twimg.com/media/Co9wv06WgAE75gw.jpg|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910063509/https://pbs.twimg.com/media/Co9wv06WgAE75gw.jpg|archivedate=2019-09-10|title=Wayback Machine|date=September 10, 2019|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 October 2016, Ahrar al-Sham arrested an alleged ISIL cell affiliated with [[Jund al-Aqsa]], Jund al-Aqsa later retaliated by arresting members of Ahrar al-Sham allegedly beating the wife and shooting the brother of one member while doing so. Ahrar al-Sham two days later on 6 October gave an ultimatum to Jund al-Aqsa to release the captured Ahrar al-Sham members, and Jund al-Aqsa countered the demand, asking that Ahrar al-Sham release the captive Jund al-Aqsa members that were allegedly part of ISIL.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/ahrar-al-sham-jund-al-aqsa-alliance-northern-hama-showing-cracks/|title=Ahrar al-Sham and Jund al-Aqsa alliance in northern Hama showing cracks|first=Paul|last=Antonopoulos|date=October 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\nOn 16 June 2017, a suicide bomber attempted to kill Saudi-cleric [[Abdullah al-Muhaysini]], whom at the time was associated with Hayat Tharir al-Sham serving on its Sharia body, after leaving a mosque in Idlib. After the attack Muhaysini said he was uninjured in an online video, and stated an invidual approached his car wearing an explosive belt and blew themselves up.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-syria-assassination/militant-saudi-cleric-survives-assassination-attempt-in-syria-idUSKBN1972AJ|title=Militant Saudi cleric survives assassination attempt in Syria|website=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\n\nOn 24 July 2017, during fighting between Ahrar al-Sham and Hayat Tahrir al-Sham, car bombs were detonated in [[Idlib]] reportedly killing 50 members of HTS, the car bombs reportedly belonged to Ahrar al-Sham.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/world/car-explosion-kills-50-al-qaida-linked-nusra-front-militants-in-syrian-city-of-idlib-3848307.html|title=Car explosion kills 50 Al-Qaida-linked Nusra Front militants in Syrian city of Idlib|website=Firstpost}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\nIn February 2018, HTS accused the [[Nour al-Din al-Zenki Movement]] of planting IEDs and assassinating HTS members in Idlib, later leading to an armed [[Syrian Liberation Front\u2013Tahrir al-Sham conflict|conflict]] between the two.\n\nOn 26 April 2018, a commander from Hayat Tahrir al-Sham was killed along with his body guard in Maarrat al-Nu\u2019man, and reportedly on the same day a commander belonging to the Syrian Liberation Front was also killed by gunmen in [[Binnish]], neither side commented on the assassinations as a cease-fire was recently signed between the two, however some sources affiliated with HTS accused the Syrian Liberation Front of carrying out the assassination against the HTS commander.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://southfront.org/two-commanders-of-hayat-tahrir-al-sham-and-syrian-liberation-front-are-assassinated-in-idlib/|title=Two Commanders Of Hay\u2019at Tahrir al-Sham And Syrian Liberation Front Are Assassinated In Idlib|date=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 April 2018, A Free Syrian Police commander was killed by an [[Improvised explosive device|IED]] in northern Idlib, on the same day hours after the bombing pro-opposition activists reported that 2 members of [[Jaysh al-Izza]] were killed by unidentified gunmen in [[Khan Shaykhun]], a commander belonging to Jaysh al-Ahrar was also killed on the same day, in response to the assassinations, including the assassination of HTS members, an HTS security official accused [[Ahrar al-Sham]] of carrying out the assassinations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://southfront.org/wave-of-assassinations-of-prominent-militant-figures-continues-in-syrias-idlib-governorate/|title=Wave Of Assassinations Of Prominent Militant Figures Continues In Syria's Idlib Governorate|date=April 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.enabbaladi.net/archives/2018/05/who-stands-behind-idlibs-assassinations-wave/|title=Who Stands behind Idlib\u2019s Assassinations Wave?|date=May 1, 2018|website=Enab Baladi}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, [[Hayat Tahrir al-Sham]] claimed to have detained members of an assassination cell composed of females in Idlib that were loyal to the Syrian government and were recruited by [[Russia]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nOn 18 June 2018, [[Jaysh al-Ahrar]]'s deputy commander was killed by gunmen in [[Saraqib]] after praying at a mosque, after his death the group released a statement saying the assassins were unknown individuals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nedaa-sy.com/en/news/6763|title=Number-Two man assassinated of \"Jaish Al Ahrar\" by unknown gunmen|date=June 18, 2018|website=Call Syria}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 June 2018, a senior HTS leader named Abu Khadija Bilal al-Khuraisat was killed by gunmen in Taramala. On the same day Jaysh al-Ahrar and the [[Sham Legion]] arrested the leader of ISIL's Idlib Province.<ref>https://www.nedaa-sy.com/en/reports/133</ref>\n\nOn 30 June 2018, HTS raided an ISIL position in Sarmin, capturing anti-tank guided missiles, the HTS-affiliated [[Ebaa News Agency]] published photos of the captured ATGMs, as well as a flag from the defunct [[Liwa Dawud]] which pledged allegiance to ISIL in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Objekt432Y/status/1013170362471739392|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910174515/https://twitter.com/Objekt432Y/status/1013170362471739392|archivedate=2019-09-10|title=zooper on Twitter: \"HTS raided an ISIS hideout in Sarmin. Among a few 14.5mm guns and ATGMs is the flag of Liwa Dawoud (\u0644\u0648\u0627\u0621 \u062f\u0627\u0648\u0648\u062f). The group was based in Sarmin until they joined ISIS in early July 2014. \"https://t.co/NnFYGmtrMh\"|date=September 10, 2019|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 July 2018, three members of the [[Syrian Liberation Front]], a merger between [[Ahrar al-Sham]] and the [[Nour al-Din al-Zenki Movement]] were killed in [[Maarrat al-Nu'man]], the Syrian Liberation Front said that the assassination was carried out by spies belonging to the Syrian government.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n===2019===\nIn January 2019, an ISIL linked media group called the Muhajireen Foundation, which provides reports on events that effect displaced ISIL fighters in Syria, released a statement warning displaced ISIL fighters in Idlib to avoid gatherings because of crackdowns by HTS and the [[Guardians of Religion Organization]] against ISIL in Idlib.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20191101180409/https://pbs.twimg.com/media/DyGqaRhV4AAvSGz?format=jpg&name=small</ref><ref>https://www.trackingterrorism.org/chatter/poster-al-muhajireen-foundation-security-alert-brothers-idlib-avoid-large-gatherings-hts-and</ref>\n\nOn 18 January 2019, a car bomb exploded at an HTS checkpoint in Idlib, reportedly resulting in the death of 10 HTS militants, on the same day gunmen wounded 3 HTS fighters, and a commander belonging to Jaysh al-Izza was killed after a bomb placed in his car by an unknown group detonated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://syrianwardaily.com/2019/01/18/syrian-war-daily-18th-of-january-2019/|title=Syrian War Daily \u2013 18th of January 2019|first=Jo\u0161ko|last=Bari\u0107|date=January 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 January 2019, a female suicide bomber believed to be part of ISIL by Hayat Tahrir al-Sham attacked the headquarters of the [[Syrian Salvation Government]], after fighting the guards outside, she blew herself up, wounding a number of people. The [[Amaq News Agency]] later denied ISIL was involved with the attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=114751|title=Suicide Attack Inside Salvation Government Building in Idleb \u2022 The Syrian Observatory For Human Rights|date=January 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pbs.twimg.com/media/DyP2wSWW0AEwwJm.jpg |title=Photo |publisher=TWIMG |accessdate=2019-10-19}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, HTS executed several ISIL members believed to be behind drive-by shootings, assassinations, and bombings. HTS reportedly in response to the violence in Idlib installed security cameras around the city to monitor the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://diyaruna.com/en_GB/articles/cnmi_di/features/2019/03/06/feature-03|title=Violence spikes in Idlib between Tahrir al-Sham, ISIS|website=Diyaruna}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March 2019, HTS raided an ISIL compound in [[Atarib]] and captured an ISIL commander as well as several stockpiles of small arms, munitions, as well as bomb making materials and explosives already manufactured by ISIL.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://syriadirect.org/news/shadow-war-between-hts-suspected-is-sleeper-cells-leaves-civilians-in-idlib-city-living-in-fear/|title=Shadow war between HTS, suspected IS sleeper cells leaves civilians in Idlib city living in fear|website=Syria direct}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March 2019, several ISIL members were able to escape from an HTS prison, reportedly after a series of Russian airstrikes in the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/1633791/isis-militants-escape-after-russian-raid-idlib|title=ISIS Militants Escape After Russian Raid on Idlib|website=Asharq AL-awsat}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, the ISIL-linked Muhajireen Foundation published an infographic showing three separate HTS actions against ISIL in Idlib. The infographic announced that several individuals held by HTS were executed publicly for allegedly belonging to ISIL and carrying out bombings. The report also included a report that two individuals were arrested in [[Nayrab]] for planting IEDs on behalf of ISIL. The report also stated that HTS raided the military headquarters of the Guardians of Religion Organization and its ally [[Ansar al-Tawhid (Syria)|Ansar al-Tawhid]], which is made up of former Jund al-Aqsa elements, in a town near [[Jisr al-Shughur]] and arrested two Egyptians from both groups for having ties to ISIL.<ref>https://pbs.twimg.com/media/EDAotSnXUAE4z80.jpg</ref><ref>https://www.trackingterrorism.org/chatter/infographic-islamic-state-supporters-al-muhajireen-foundation-unofficial-violations-apostate</ref>\n\nOn 5 August 2019, a Tunisian Guardians of Religion Organization commander was assassinated by unknown perpetrators in [[Taftanaz]], with some pro-opposition activists claiming the assassins were ISIL linked.\n<ref name=\"auto5aug\">{{cite web|url=https://almasdarnews.com/article/key-foreign-jihadist-commander-assassinated-in-idlib/|title=Key foreign jihadist commander assassinated in Idlib|website=Al-Masdar}}</ref>\n\n===2020===\nOn 18 March, Turkish troops entered the de-escalation zone to reopen the M4 highway previosly blocked by [[Hayat Tahrir al-Sham]] and jihadist factions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=157700&__cf_chl_jschl_tk__=8bb84c3053d1c85af5c2891a998580f8f13659df-1585881380-0-ATNWbVOtQtaiQPjwFGUxLY9GIHQzrS80uZtN3NAbzlXnVSFdXpQRr9XpPk0dSW7joOpFsbLuGU5BXxkNU8pgOvZSfXxCheTTQKEOViZEH532D4B6rPMjlTybmbSBTFAdh82UvktITJ0Ckf5s4BOV7x9RelqNaBGyrGb2QA945P9uY_kTB1-WyuslZL7Xu_cE0Fw0VMI1YtGIOT8RXiqh5s1T08uP_aKkqtvGj4MNpd_Ti_o9MsKxSalIjbX8PMQ_tRwnpwt5I3wqRyOp7tnJ1bvaQNwuL_XqalG2JF776FR5|work=[[Syrian Observatory for Human Rights]]|title=Under HTS\u2019s supervision, Turkish forces set up guard posts and conduct patrol on their own|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> An Ahrar al-Sham commander was killed after a roadside bomb went off while he was driving near Jisr al-Shughur.<ref name=\"auto18march\">{{cite web|url=https://almasdarnews.com/article/militant-commander-assassinated-in-western-idlib/|title=Militant commander assassinated in western Idlib|website=Al-Masdar}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, two Turkish soldiers were killed and a third was wounded by an attack that the Turkish Defense Ministry claimed was carried out by unamed radical groups.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/rocket-attack-northwest-syria-kills-turkish-soldiers-200320041200347.html|work=Al-Jazeera|title=Rocket attack in northwest Syria kills two Turkish soldiers|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref>[https://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-retaliates-after-attack-kills-troops-in-idlib-153125 Turkey retaliates after attack kills troops in Idlib]</ref> [[Guardians of Religion Organization|Hurras al Dien]] a organization close to [[Al Qaeda]] was accused of carrying out the attack.<ref>[http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=157678 IED explosions target Turkish column on the M4 road west Idlib kill two Turkish soldiers]</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 2020, a mine detonated while a Turkish military convoy was passing through the town of Sufahan on the M4 Highway resulting in two Turkish soldiers wounded.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=158003|work=[[Syrian Observatory for Human Rights]]|title=\nTurkish forces sustain human and material losses after entering a mine field south of Idlib|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> On the same day unknown gunmen tried to kidnap a Rebel commander of the Saraqeb Front in Idlib city, wounding him.<ref>[http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=158061 Unidentified gunmen open fire on opposition commander in Idlib city center]</ref>\n\nOn 4 April 2020, a field commander of [[Ahrar al-Sham]] was killed by a mine in Sufahan, in southern Idlib.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=159464|work=[[Syrian Observatory for Human Rights]]|title=\nCommander of \u201cAhrar Al-Sham\u201d killed in landmine explosion in Jabal Al-Zawiyah, while regime forces fire rockets on Aleppo and Latakia|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[SDF insurgency in Northern Aleppo]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Syrian Civil War]]\n[[Category:Idlib Governorate]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Insurgency in Idlib\n| partof      = the [[Syrian Civil War]]\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| date        = 2015-Present\n| place       = [[Idlib Governorate]], [[Syria]]\n| status      = \n| combatant1  = \n{{flagdeco|Syria}} [[Syrian Government]] loyalists\n'''Supported by:'''\n{{flag|Russia}}<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.qasioun-news.com/news/show/145253/%20/%3E|title=HTS Detains Assassination Cell Led By Females In Idlib|website=qasioun-news.com}}</ref>\n----\n[[Wrath of Olives Operations Room]] ({{small|against [[Turkish-backed Free Syrian Army|TFSA]] and [[National Front for Liberation|NFL]]}})<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hawarnews.com/ar/haber/d8bad8b6d8a8-d8a7d984d8b2d98ad8aad988d986-d8aad986d981d8b0-d8b9d985d984d98ad8a9-d8acd986d988d8a8-d8a5d8afd984d8a8-h4441.html|title=The Operation Anger of Olives indicated that their forces carried out an operation in the southern countryside of Idlib, destroying a point of the Failaq al-Sham mercenaries and killing two of its mercenaries, stressing that the operation was in response to the ongoing violations by the mercenaries against the people of Afrin.|work=[[Hawar News Agency]]|date=1 July 2018}}</ref><br>{{flagicon image|Flag of Jaysh al-Thuwar.svg}} [[Army of Revolutionaries]] ({{small|Army of Conquest claim, 2016}})\n| combatant2  = {{flagicon image|Flag of the Syrian Salvation Government.svg}} [[Syrian Salvation Government]]\n*{{flagicon image|Flag of Hayat Tahrir al-Sham.svg}} [[Tahrir al-Sham]]<br>\n{{flagicon image|Guardians Of Religion INFOBOX flag.png}} [[Guardians of Religion Organization]] <small>(Sometimes)</small><br>\n{{Flagicon image|Emblem of the Jaish al-Fatah.svg}} [[Army of Conquest]] <small>(dissolved in 2017)</small>\n*{{flagicon image|Flag of Ahrar ash-Sham.svg}} [[Ahrar al-Sham]] <small>(2015-2017)</small>\n----\n{{flagdeco|Syrian Opposition}} [[Jaysh al-Izza]]<br>{{flagicon image|Al-Liwaa.svg}} [[Jaysh al-Ahrar]]<br>{{flag|Turkey}}\n| combatant3  = {{flagdeco|ISIL}} [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]\n*Wilayat Idlib\n**{{flagicon image|Flag of Jund al-Aqsa.svg}} [[Jund al-Aqsa]]\n**{{flagicon image|LiwaDawudFlag.jpg}} [[Liwa Dawud]] remnants\n----\n{{flagicon image|AnsaralTawhidFlag.png}} [[Ansar al-Tawhid (Syria)|Ansar al-Tawhid]]<br>{{flagicon image|Guardians Of Religion INFOBOX flag.png}} [[Guardians of Religion Organization]] <small>(Sometimes)</small>\n| combatant4 =\n{{flagdeco|Syrian Opposition}} [[Syrian Liberation Front]]\n*{{flagicon image|Al-Liwaa.svg}} [[Nour al-Din al-Zenki Movement]]\n*{{flagicon image|Flag of Ahrar ash-Sham.svg}} [[Ahrar al-Sham]] \n| commander1  = Unknown\n| commander2  = {{flagicon image|Flag of Hayat Tahrir al-Sham.svg}} [[Abdullah al-Muhaysini]]<br>{{flagicon image|Flag of Hayat Tahrir al-Sham.svg}} Abu Khadija Bilal al-Khuraisat{{KIA}}<br>{{flagicon image|Guardians Of Religion INFOBOX flag.png}} Abu Al-Walid al-Tunisi{{KIA}}\n| commander3  = {{flagdeco|ISIL}} Ali Nejdet Aldiri{{POW}}<br>{{flagdeco|ISIL}} Said al-Hunaiti{{POW}}<br>{{flagdeco|ISIL}} Abu Khattab Kafr-Nabudah{{POW}}\n| commander4  = {{flagicon image|Flag of Ahrar ash-Sham.svg}} Ala Abu Ahmed{{KIA}}\n| units1      = {{flagdeco|Syria}} Government loyalists<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/more-rebel-fighters-assassinated-in-idlib-amid-escalated-tensions/|title=More rebel fighters assassinated in Idlib amid escalated tensions|first=Zen|last=Adra|date=July 29, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Military Intelligence Directorate (Syria)|Military Intelligence Directorate]]\n**Female unit\n| units2      = [[Syrian Salvation Government]]\n*Police forces\n| units3      = Unknown \n| units4      = Unknown\n| strength1   = \n| strength2   = \n| casualties1 = \n| casualties2 = \n| casualties3 = \n| notes       = \n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Syrian Civil War}}\n}}\nThe '''Insurgency in Idlib''' is an ongoing insurgency in rebel-held areas in the [[Idlib Governorate]] between multiple factions ranging from supporters of the [[Syrian government]] to rival opposition elements to supporters and members of the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2018/07/islamic-state-targets-rival-jihadists-and-islamists-in-northern-syria.php|title=Islamic State targets rival jihadists and Islamists in northern Syria &#124; FDD's Long War Journal|date=July 15, 2018|website=longwarjournal.org}}</ref> The insurgency is marked by assassinations, bombings as well as light armed confrontations with small arms and raids.\n\n==Timeline==\n===2015===\nIn July 2015, the [[Islamic Front (Syria)|Islamic Front]]'s [[Twitter]] account posted that the group had clashed with an ISIL cell in Idlib.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pbs.twimg.com/media/CKq50Y9WwAAAolK.jpg|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910063013/https://pbs.twimg.com/media/CKq50Y9WwAAAolK.jpg|archivedate=2019-09-10|title=Wayback Machine|date=September 10, 2019|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nOn 31 March 2016, the [[Army of Conquest]] claimed to have captured members of a cell belonging to [[Jaysh al-Thuwar]], an Arab component of the [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] in Idlib that was  reportedly conducting assassinations and kidnappings in the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://orient-news.net/en/news_show/107664/0/news_images/16_3/banners/en/cat_show/50/tamplate/Default/LA/css/all-stylesheets.css|title=Jaysh al-Fatth captures a Jaysh al-Thuwar cell|website=Orient-news.net}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 June 2016, the Army of Conquest's police division published a statement saying that the group's police arrested members of a cell that were helping to smuggle members of ISIL from [[Turkey]] into Idlib.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pbs.twimg.com/media/Clk_lDOWAAEB8uU.jpg|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910064101/https://pbs.twimg.com/media/Clk_lDOWAAEB8uU.jpg|archivedate=2019-09-10|title=Wayback Machine|date=September 10, 2019|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 August 2016, the Army of Conquest coalition released a statement saying the coalition's security forces dismantled an ISIL cell in Idlib after 20 days of surveillance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pbs.twimg.com/media/Co9wv06WgAE75gw.jpg|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910063509/https://pbs.twimg.com/media/Co9wv06WgAE75gw.jpg|archivedate=2019-09-10|title=Wayback Machine|date=September 10, 2019|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 October 2016, Ahrar al-Sham arrested an alleged ISIL cell affiliated with [[Jund al-Aqsa]], Jund al-Aqsa later retaliated by arresting members of Ahrar al-Sham allegedly beating the wife and shooting the brother of one member while doing so. Ahrar al-Sham two days later on 6 October gave an ultimatum to Jund al-Aqsa to release the captured Ahrar al-Sham members, and Jund al-Aqsa countered the demand, asking that Ahrar al-Sham release the captive Jund al-Aqsa members that were allegedly part of ISIL.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/ahrar-al-sham-jund-al-aqsa-alliance-northern-hama-showing-cracks/|title=Ahrar al-Sham and Jund al-Aqsa alliance in northern Hama showing cracks|first=Paul|last=Antonopoulos|date=October 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\nOn 16 June 2017, a suicide bomber attempted to kill Saudi-cleric [[Abdullah al-Muhaysini]], whom at the time was associated with Hayat Tharir al-Sham serving on its Sharia body, after leaving a mosque in Idlib. After the attack Muhaysini said he was uninjured in an online video, and stated an invidual apporached his car wearing an explosive belt and blew themselves up.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-syria-assassination/militant-saudi-cleric-survives-assassination-attempt-in-syria-idUSKBN1972AJ|title=Militant Saudi cleric survives assassination attempt in Syria|website=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\n\nOn 24 July 2017, during fighting between Ahrar al-Sham and Hayat Tahrir al-Sham, car bombs were detonated in [[Idlib]] reportedly killing 50 members of HTS, the car bombs reportedly belonged to Ahrar al-Sham.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/world/car-explosion-kills-50-al-qaida-linked-nusra-front-militants-in-syrian-city-of-idlib-3848307.html|title=Car explosion kills 50 Al-Qaida-linked Nusra Front militants in Syrian city of Idlib|website=Firstpost}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\nIn February 2018, HTS accused the [[Nour al-Din al-Zenki Movement]] of planting IEDs and assassinating HTS members in Idlib, later leading to an armed [[Syrian Liberation Front\u2013Tahrir al-Sham conflict|conflict]] between the two.\n\nOn 26 April 2018, a commander from Hayat Tahrir al-Sham was killed along with his body guard in Maarrat al-Nu\u2019man, and reportedly on the same day a commander belonging to the Syrian Liberation Front was also killed by gunmen in [[Binnish]], neither side commented on the assassinations as a cease-fire was recently signed between the two, however some sources affiliated with HTS accused the Syrian Liberation Front of carrying out the assassination against the HTS commander.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://southfront.org/two-commanders-of-hayat-tahrir-al-sham-and-syrian-liberation-front-are-assassinated-in-idlib/|title=Two Commanders Of Hay\u2019at Tahrir al-Sham And Syrian Liberation Front Are Assassinated In Idlib|date=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 April 2018, A Free Syrian Police commander was killed by an [[Improvised explosive device|IED]] in northern Idlib, on the same day hours after the bombing pro-opposition activists reported that 2 members of [[Jaysh al-Izza]] were killed by unidentified gunmen in [[Khan Shaykhun]], a commander belonging to Jaysh al-Ahrar was also killed on the same day, in response to the assassinations, including the assassination of HTS members, an HTS security official accused [[Ahrar al-Sham]] of carrying out the assassinations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://southfront.org/wave-of-assassinations-of-prominent-militant-figures-continues-in-syrias-idlib-governorate/|title=Wave Of Assassinations Of Prominent Militant Figures Continues In Syria's Idlib Governorate|date=April 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.enabbaladi.net/archives/2018/05/who-stands-behind-idlibs-assassinations-wave/|title=Who Stands behind Idlib\u2019s Assassinations Wave?|date=May 1, 2018|website=Enab Baladi}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, [[Hayat Tahrir al-Sham]] claimed to have detained members of an assassination cell composed of females in Idlib that were loyal to the Syrian government and were recruited by [[Russia]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nOn 18 June 2018, [[Jaysh al-Ahrar]]'s deputy commander was killed by gunmen in [[Saraqib]] after praying at a mosque, after his death the group released a statement saying the assassins were unknown individuals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nedaa-sy.com/en/news/6763|title=Number-Two man assassinated of \"Jaish Al Ahrar\" by unknown gunmen|date=June 18, 2018|website=Call Syria}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 June 2018, a senior HTS leader named Abu Khadija Bilal al-Khuraisat was killed by gunmen in Taramala. On the same day Jaysh al-Ahrar and the [[Sham Legion]] arrested the leader of ISIL's Idlib Province.<ref>https://www.nedaa-sy.com/en/reports/133</ref>\n\nOn 30 June 2018, HTS raided an ISIL position in Sarmin, capturing anti-tank guided missiles, the HTS-affiliated [[Ebaa News Agency]] published photos of the captured ATGMs, as well as a flag from the defunct [[Liwa Dawud]] which pledged allegiance to ISIL in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Objekt432Y/status/1013170362471739392|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190910174515/https://twitter.com/Objekt432Y/status/1013170362471739392|archivedate=2019-09-10|title=zooper on Twitter: \"HTS raided an ISIS hideout in Sarmin. Among a few 14.5mm guns and ATGMs is the flag of Liwa Dawoud (\u0644\u0648\u0627\u0621 \u062f\u0627\u0648\u0648\u062f). The group was based in Sarmin until they joined ISIS in early July 2014. \"https://t.co/NnFYGmtrMh\"|date=September 10, 2019|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 July 2018, three members of the [[Syrian Liberation Front]], a merger between [[Ahrar al-Sham]] and the [[Nour al-Din al-Zenki Movement]] were killed in [[Maarrat al-Nu'man]], the Syrian Liberation Front said that the assassination was carried out by spies belonging to the Syrian government.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n===2019===\nIn January 2019, an ISIL linked media group called the Muhajireen Foundation, which provides reports on events that effect displaced ISIL fighters in Syria, released a statement warning displaced ISIL fighters in Idlib to avoid gatherings because of crackdowns by HTS and the [[Guardians of Religion Organization]] against ISIL in Idlib.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20191101180409/https://pbs.twimg.com/media/DyGqaRhV4AAvSGz?format=jpg&name=small</ref><ref>https://www.trackingterrorism.org/chatter/poster-al-muhajireen-foundation-security-alert-brothers-idlib-avoid-large-gatherings-hts-and</ref>\n\nOn 18 January 2019, a car bomb exploded at an HTS checkpoint in Idlib, reportedly resulting in the death of 10 HTS militants, on the same day gunmen wounded 3 HTS fighters, and a commander belonging to Jaysh al-Izza was killed after a bomb placed in his car by an unknown group detonated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://syrianwardaily.com/2019/01/18/syrian-war-daily-18th-of-january-2019/|title=Syrian War Daily \u2013 18th of January 2019|first=Jo\u0161ko|last=Bari\u0107|date=January 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 January 2019, a female suicide bomber believed to be part of ISIL by Hayat Tahrir al-Sham attacked the headquarters of the [[Syrian Salvation Government]], after fighting the guards outside, she blew herself up, wounding a number of people. The [[Amaq News Agency]] later denied ISIL was involved with the attack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=114751|title=Suicide Attack Inside Salvation Government Building in Idleb \u2022 The Syrian Observatory For Human Rights|date=January 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pbs.twimg.com/media/DyP2wSWW0AEwwJm.jpg |title=Photo |publisher=TWIMG |accessdate=2019-10-19}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, HTS executed several ISIL members believed to be behind drive-by shootings, assassinations, and bombings. HTS reportedly in response to the violence in Idlib installed security cameras around the city to monitor the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://diyaruna.com/en_GB/articles/cnmi_di/features/2019/03/06/feature-03|title=Violence spikes in Idlib between Tahrir al-Sham, ISIS|website=Diyaruna}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March 2019, HTS raided an ISIL compound in [[Atarib]] and captured an ISIL commander as well as several stockpiles of small arms, munitions, as well as bomb making materials and explosives already manufactured by ISIL.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://syriadirect.org/news/shadow-war-between-hts-suspected-is-sleeper-cells-leaves-civilians-in-idlib-city-living-in-fear/|title=Shadow war between HTS, suspected IS sleeper cells leaves civilians in Idlib city living in fear|website=Syria direct}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March 2019, several ISIL members were able to escape from an HTS prison, reportedly after a series of Russian airstrikes in the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/1633791/isis-militants-escape-after-russian-raid-idlib|title=ISIS Militants Escape After Russian Raid on Idlib|website=Asharq AL-awsat}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, the ISIL-linked Muhajireen Foundation published an infographic showing three separate HTS actions against ISIL in Idlib. The infographic announced that several individuals held by HTS were executed publicly for allegedly belonging to ISIL and carrying out bombings. The report also included a report that two individuals were arrested in [[Nayrab]] for planting IEDs on behalf of ISIL. The report also stated that HTS raided the military headquarters of the Guardians of Religion Organization and its ally [[Ansar al-Tawhid (Syria)|Ansar al-Tawhid]], which is made up of former Jund al-Aqsa elements, in a town near [[Jisr al-Shughur]] and arrested two Egyptians from both groups for having ties to ISIL.<ref>https://pbs.twimg.com/media/EDAotSnXUAE4z80.jpg</ref><ref>https://www.trackingterrorism.org/chatter/infographic-islamic-state-supporters-al-muhajireen-foundation-unofficial-violations-apostate</ref>\n\nOn 5 August 2019, a Tunisian Guardians of Religion Organization commander was assassinated by unknown perpetrators in [[Taftanaz]], with some pro-opposition activists claiming the assassins were ISIL linked.\n<ref name=\"auto5aug\">{{cite web|url=https://almasdarnews.com/article/key-foreign-jihadist-commander-assassinated-in-idlib/|title=Key foreign jihadist commander assassinated in Idlib|website=Al-Masdar}}</ref>\n\n===2020===\nOn 18 March, Turkish troops entered the de-escalation zone to reopen the M4 highway previosly blocked by [[Hayat Tahrir al-Sham]] and jihadist factions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=157700&__cf_chl_jschl_tk__=8bb84c3053d1c85af5c2891a998580f8f13659df-1585881380-0-ATNWbVOtQtaiQPjwFGUxLY9GIHQzrS80uZtN3NAbzlXnVSFdXpQRr9XpPk0dSW7joOpFsbLuGU5BXxkNU8pgOvZSfXxCheTTQKEOViZEH532D4B6rPMjlTybmbSBTFAdh82UvktITJ0Ckf5s4BOV7x9RelqNaBGyrGb2QA945P9uY_kTB1-WyuslZL7Xu_cE0Fw0VMI1YtGIOT8RXiqh5s1T08uP_aKkqtvGj4MNpd_Ti_o9MsKxSalIjbX8PMQ_tRwnpwt5I3wqRyOp7tnJ1bvaQNwuL_XqalG2JF776FR5|work=[[Syrian Observatory for Human Rights]]|title=Under HTS\u2019s supervision, Turkish forces set up guard posts and conduct patrol on their own|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> An Ahrar al-Sham commander was killed after a roadside bomb went off while he was driving near Jisr al-Shughur.<ref name=\"auto18march\">{{cite web|url=https://almasdarnews.com/article/militant-commander-assassinated-in-western-idlib/|title=Militant commander assassinated in western Idlib|website=Al-Masdar}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, two Turkish soldiers were killed and a third was wounded by an attack that the Turkish Defense Ministry claimed was carried out by unamed radical groups.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/rocket-attack-northwest-syria-kills-turkish-soldiers-200320041200347.html|work=Al-Jazeera|title=Rocket attack in northwest Syria kills two Turkish soldiers|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref>[https://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-retaliates-after-attack-kills-troops-in-idlib-153125 Turkey retaliates after attack kills troops in Idlib]</ref> [[Guardians of Religion Organization|Hurras al Dien]] a organization close to [[Al Qaeda]] was accused of carrying out the attack.<ref>[http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=157678 IED explosions target Turkish column on the M4 road west Idlib kill two Turkish soldiers]</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 2020, a mine detonated while a Turkish military convoy was passing through the town of Sufahan on the M4 Highway resulting in two Turkish soldiers wounded.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=158003|work=[[Syrian Observatory for Human Rights]]|title=\nTurkish forces sustain human and material losses after entering a mine field south of Idlib|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> On the same day unknown gunmen tried to kidnap a Rebel commander of the Saraqeb Front in Idlib city, wounding him.<ref>[http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=158061 Unidentified gunmen open fire on opposition commander in Idlib city center]</ref>\n\nOn 4 April 2020, a field commander of [[Ahrar al-Sham]] was killed by a mine in Sufahan, in southern Idlib.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=159464|work=[[Syrian Observatory for Human Rights]]|title=\nCommander of \u201cAhrar Al-Sham\u201d killed in landmine explosion in Jabal Al-Zawiyah, while regime forces fire rockets on Aleppo and Latakia|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[SDF insurgency in Northern Aleppo]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Syrian Civil War]]\n[[Category:Idlib Governorate]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "apporached->approached -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Insurgency_in_Idlib"}
{"title_page": "Albanian nobility", "text_new": "The '''Albanian nobility''' was an [[elite]] hereditary ruling class in [[Albania]], parts of the western [[Balkans]] and later in parts of the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] world. The Albanian nobility was composed of landowners of vast areas, often in allegiance to states like the [[Byzantine Empire]], various [[Serbia in the Middle Ages|Serbian states]], the [[Republic of Venice]], the [[Ottoman Empire]] and the [[Kingdom of Naples]] in addition to the [[Albanian principalities]]. They often used Byzantine, Latin or Slavic titles,<ref>{{cite book|title=Bulgarian historical review|year=2003|publisher=Pub. House of the Bulgarian Academy of Sciences|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lD5pAAAAMAAJ|page=164|quote=Albanian nobility used intensively a titulature* of Byzantine, Latin or Slavic origins}}</ref> such as [[sebastokrator]], [[Despot (court title)|despot]], [[dux]], [[Count|conte]] and [[\u017dupan|zupan]].\n\n== Byzantine Empire ==\n{{Further|Albania under the Byzantine Empire}}\nThe [[Muzaka family]] was loyal to the [[Byzantine Empire]]. For their loyalty to Byzantium, the head of the family [[Andrea II Muzaka]] gained the title of [[Despot (court title)|Despot]] in 1335, while other Muzakas continued to pursue careers in Byzantine administration in Constantinople.<ref name=Anamalipp252-255>{{citation|last=Anamali|first=Sk\u00ebnder|title=Historia e popullit shqiptar n\u00eb kat\u00ebr v\u00ebllime|volume=I|year=2002|page=252|publisher=Botimet Toena|language=Albanian|oclc=52411919}}</ref>\n\n== Principality of Arbanon ==\n{{main|Principality of Arbanon}}\nThe first Albanian state in the Middle Ages it was ruled by the [[Progon family|Progoni family]] and extended from the [[Drin (river)|Drin]] river to the southern boundary of the [[Lake Ohrid|Ohrid lake]]. Its rulers were known in Catholic sources with the titles of judices, while in Byzantine ones the titles mentioned are those of the grand [[archon]] and the [[panhypersebastos]].\n\n== Kingdom of Serbia ==\nWhen [[Durr\u00ebs]] was captured by the [[Kingdom of Serbia (medieval)|Kingdom of Serbia]], [[Stephen Uro\u0161 II Milutin of Serbia|Milutin]] was titled the King of Albania while his rule was occasionally recognized by Albanian noblemen around Durr\u00ebs.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Rad Jugoslavenske akademije znanosti i umjetnosti]]|issue=257|year=1937|publisher=Yugoslav Academy of Sciences and Arts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i9wVAQAAIAAJ|page=259|language=Serbian|quote=Kasnije, kad je Dra\u010d pao u srpske ruke, nosi\u0107e kralj Milutin naslov kralja Arbanije.|title=Rad Jugoslavenske akademije znanosti i umjetnosti}}{{title missing|date=June 2016}}{{author missing|date=June 2016}}</ref> Many Albanian noblemen were included in the feudal hierarchy of the Kingdom of Serbia and had titles and privileges of \u017eupans, voivodas or [[kaznac]]s.<ref>{{cite book| last= Bogdanovi\u0107| first= Dimitrije| authorlink = Dimitrije Bogdanovi\u0107| editor= Antonije Isakovi\u0107| title= Knjiga o Kosovu| url = http://www.kosovo.net/sk/rastko-kosovo/istorija/knjiga_o_kosovu/index.html| accessdate    = January 9, 2011| volume    = 2| origyear  = 1984|date=November 2000| publisher = [[Serbian Academy of Sciences and Arts]]| location  = Belgrade| language  = Serbian| chapter   = Albanski pokreti 1908\u20131912.|trans-chapter=| chapterurl= http://www.kosovo.net/sk/rastko-kosovo/istorija/knjiga_o_kosovu/bogdanovic-kosovo_2.html| quote=  srpskog kralja Milutina [1282\u20131321]... vlast srpskog kralja priznavali su povremeno i albanski velika\u0161i u zale\u0111u Dra\u010da...Jo\u0161 u doba kralja Milutina albanski feudalci ce uklju\u010duju u feudalni poredak srpske dr\u017eave sa zvanjima i beneficijama \u017eupana, vojvode ili kaznaca.}}</ref>\n\n== Serbian Empire ==\n{{Further|Albania under the Serbian Empire}}\nAlbanian nobility was included into hierarchy of the feudal system of [[Serbian Empire]] without any discrimination and participated in the work of the highest government institutions, where Albanian [[archons]] had the same rights as the [[Serbian nobility]] had.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bogdanovi\u0107|first=Dimitrije| authorlink = Dimitrije Bogdanovi\u0107| editor=Antonije Isakovi\u0107|title=Knjiga o Kosovu| url = http://www.kosovo.net/sk/rastko-kosovo/istorija/knjiga_o_kosovu/index.html| accessdate    = January 9, 2011| volume    = 2| origyear  = 1984|date=November 2000| publisher = [[Serbian Academy of Sciences and Arts]]| location  = Belgrade| language  = Serbian| chapter   = Albanski pokreti 1908\u20131912.|trans-chapter=| chapterurl= http://www.kosovo.net/sk/rastko-kosovo/istorija/knjiga_o_kosovu/bogdanovic-kosovo_2.html| quote=  U Du\u0161anovom carstvu albanske zemlje i velika\u0161i Albanije obuhva\u0107eni su bez ikakvog izdvajanja i diskriminacije hijerarhijskim feudalnim sistemom....Politi\u010dka integracija Albanaca u srednjovekovnoj srpskoj dr\u017eavi izvr\u0161ena je u okviru feudalnog sistema bez diskriminacije prema albanskoj vlasteli. Sa svojim starim ili novim zvanjima, ste\u010denim ili tek dobijenim povlasticama, sa ba\u0161tinama, pronijama i drugim feudalnim pravima albanski feudalci, u meri u kojoj su ulazili u srpsku dr\u017eavu, bili su aktivan \u010dinilac te dr\u017eave. U titulama srpskih kraljeva odnosno careva, kao \u0161to smo videli, albanski narod je do\u0161ao i do svojevrsnog dr\u017eavnopravnog legitimiteta. Ovaj ce legitimitet izra\u017eavao i u pravima albanske vlastele da u\u010destvuje u radu najvi\u0161ih organa vlasti srpske dr\u017eave, srpskih sabora. Ve\u0107 sa \u0161irenjem granica srpske dr\u017eave preko gr\u010dkih i albanskih oblasti, kako je primetio Nikola Radoj\u010di\u0107, javilo ce pitanje o u\u010destvovanju Grka i Albanaca na srpskim saborima; gr\u010dki i albanski arhonti su i u\u010destvovali u radu sabora sa svim pravima srpske vlastele. }}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Uq0rAQAAIAAJ \u0423 \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435 \u0458\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0433 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440\u0430 \u0441\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0435 \u0434\u0440\u0436\u0430\u0432\u0435 \u0443 \u0441\u0440\u0435\u0434\u045a\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0443 \u0410\u043b- \u0431\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0443 \u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0442\u043f\u0443\u043d\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0432\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0446\u0430\u0440\u0430 \u0421\u0442\u0435\u0444\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u0414\u0443\u0448\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u0430\u0440\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0448\u043a\u0430 \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0458\u0435 \u0430\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043d \u0438 \u0432\u0440\u043b\u043e \u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u0458\u0430\u043d \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u0447\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043b\u0430\u0446 \u0443 \u0437\u0435\u043c\u0459\u0438.], p.42 \u2013 Glas, \u0422\u043e\u043c 338, Srpska akademija nauka i umetnosti, 1983</ref> [[Stephen Uro\u0161 IV Du\u0161an of Serbia|Serbian emperor]] wanted to gain the support of the Albanian nobility so he confirmed the privileges Kruje had been granted by the [[Byzantine Empire]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Christos Soulis|first=George|title=The Serbs and Byzantium during the reign of Tsar Stephen Du\u0161an (1331\u20131355) and his successors|year=1984|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NXFpAAAAMAAJ|page=136|quote=The chrysobull that Dusan issued in June 13h3, by which he confirmed the privileges of Kroja that had been granted by the Byzantine emperors, clearly indicates that the Serbian ruler sought to win the support of the Albanian nobility. From the evidence of this document we may assume that Du\u0161an entrusted to the local nobility the administration of various Albanian cities|isbn=9780884021377}}</ref>\n\n== Ottoman Empire ==\n{{Further|History of Albania during Ottoman administration}}\nA decisive point of the relation of Albanian nobility with Ottoman Empire was the [[Battle of Savra]] in 1385.<ref>{{cite book|title=Studia Albanica, Volume 38, Issue 1|year=2005|publisher=Acad\u00e9mie des sciences de la R\u00e9publique Populaire d'Albanie, Institut d'histoire, Institut de linguistique et litt\u00e9rature.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y4RpAAAAMAAJ|authors =Universiteti Shtet\u00ebror i Tiran\u00ebs. Instituti i Historis\u00eb e Gjuh\u00ebsis\u00eb, Instituti i Gjuh\u00ebsis\u00eb dhe i Let\u00ebrsis\u00eb (Akademia e Shkencave e RPS t\u00eb Shqip\u00ebris\u00eb), Akademia e Shkencave e RPSH. Instituti i Ghuh\u00ebsis\u00eb dhe i Let\u00ebrsis\u00eb, Instituti i Historis\u00eb (Akademia e Shkencave e RPS t\u00eb Shqip\u00ebris\u00eb)|accessdate=26 March 2012|page=85|quote=A turning point in the first contacts between the Albanian nobility and the Ottomans was the Battle of Savra (ca. 1385).}}</ref> After the Battle of Savra Albanian nobility became vassals of the Ottoman Empire.<ref>{{cite book|title=Studia Albanica, Volume 38, Issue 1|year=2005|publisher=Acad\u00e9mie des sciences de la R\u00e9publique Populaire d'Albanie, Institut d'histoire, Institut de linguistique et litt\u00e9rature.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y4RpAAAAMAAJ|authors =Universiteti Shtet\u00ebror i Tiran\u00ebs. Instituti i Historis\u00eb e Gjuh\u00ebsis\u00eb, Instituti i Gjuh\u00ebsis\u00eb dhe i Let\u00ebrsis\u00eb (Akademia e Shkencave e RPS t\u00eb Shqip\u00ebris\u00eb), Akademia e Shkencave e RPSH. Instituti i Ghuh\u00ebsis\u00eb dhe i Let\u00ebrsis\u00eb, Instituti i Historis\u00eb (Akademia e Shkencave e RPS t\u00eb Shqip\u00ebris\u00eb)|accessdate=26 March 2012|page=85|quote=After the Battle of Savra Albanian princes became vassals of the Ottomans.}}</ref>\n\nAlbanian nobility did not fight against Ottomans with united and compact forces like Serbian and Bulgarian aristocracy, but with small independent local rulers.<ref>{{cite book|last=Skendi|first=Stavro|title=Balkan cultural studies|year=1980|publisher=East European Monographs|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JWBiAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Albanian+nobility%22&dq=%22Albanian+nobility%22|accessdate=26 March 2012|page=172|quote=...the Bulgarian and Serbian aristocracies...In the first place, the Albanian feudal lords did not fight against the Ottomans, as the Bulgarians and Serbs in an orderly battle, with united and compact forces.|isbn=9780914710660}}</ref> Therefore, the Ottomans, who have been since claimed to be \"brutal and cruel\" to the Serbian and Bulgarian nobility, might have been conciliatory with the Albanian nobility.<ref>{{cite book|last=Skendi|first=Stavro|title=Balkan cultural studies|year=1980|publisher=East European Monographs|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JWBiAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Albanian+nobility%22&dq=%22Albanian+nobility%22|accessdate=26 March 2012|page=172|quote=One might wonder why the Ottomans, who were so harsh on the Bulgarian and Serbian aristocracies, were so conciliatory with the Albanian nobility.|isbn=9780914710660}}</ref>\n\nWhen Albania became part of the [[Ottoman Empire]], it was divided into [[sanjaks]] with numerous [[timars]]. Many members of the Albanian nobility held high rank positions within Ottoman the hierarchy, like [[Skanderbeg]] and [[Ballaban Badera]] who were Ottoman sanjakbeys.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omda.bg/imir/studies/alban_id9.html |title=Albanian identities |first=Antonina |last=Zhelyazkova |trans-title= |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.omda.bg%2Fimir%2Fstudies%2Falban_id9.html&date=2011-04-03 |archivedate=April 3, 2011 |accessdate=April 3, 2011 |quote=In 1440, he was promoted to sancakbey of Debar |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=\u0130nalc\u0131k  |first=Halil |authorlink=Halil \u0130nalc\u0131k |title=From empire to republic : essays on Ottoman and Turkish social history |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kIhpAAAAMAAJ|publisher=  Isis Press |location= Istanbul |isbn=9789754280807 |oclc=34985150 |page=88 |quote=Balaban Aga, qui a accord\u00e9 des timar \u00e0 ses propres soldats dans la Basse- Dibra et dans la \u00c7ermeni\u00e7a, ainsi qu'\u00e0 son neveu \u00e0 Mati, doit \u00eatre ce m\u00eame Balaban Aga, sancakbeyi d'Ohrid, connu pour ses batailles sanglantes contre Skanderbeg. |year=1995 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Balkans: a short history from Greek times to the present day, Volume 1972, Part 2 |last=H\u00f6sch |first=Peter |year=1972 |publisher=Crane, Russak |location= |isbn= 978-0-8448-0072-1 |page=96 |url= https://books.google.com/?id=2RoXAQAAIAAJ&q=sanjak+of+dibra&dq=sanjak+of+dibra|accessdate= April 4, 2011}}</ref> Some members of the Albanian nobility were Ottoman [[timariots]].<ref>{{cite book|title=AARP, art and archaeology research papers|year=1975|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IXVXAAAAMAAJ|page=61|quote=Some timars were acquired by members of the Albanian nobility,}}</ref> Through the implementation of the [[Timar#Timar system|timar system]] the Albanian nobility was absorbed into the Ottoman military class within not more than two generations.<ref>{{Citation |last=Schmitt |first=Oliver Jens|editor= |title=Religion und Kultur im albanischsprachigen S\u00fcdosteuropa |url= https://books.google.com/?id=aCdYHU9PtiIC&pg=PA20&dq=albanian+nobility#v=onepage&q=albanian%20nobility&f=false |volume= 4 |year=2010 |publisher= Lang |location=Frankfurt am Main, Berlin, Bern, Bruxelles, New York, Oxford, Wien |isbn= 978-3-631-60295-9 |page=22|quote= After the adoption of timar system, the absorption of Albanian nobility into Ottoman military class did not take more than two generations }}</ref> They adopted the [[List of Ottoman titles and appellations|Ottoman titles]] like [[Agha (Ottoman Empire)|aga]], [[bey]] or [[Pashas|pasha]].\n\n== Venetian Republic ==\n{{Further|Venetian Albania}}\n\nDuring the period of crisis for the Ottoman Empire after the [[Battle of Ankara]] in 1402 several Ottoman vassals from Albania including  [[Gjon Kastrioti]], Niketas Thopia and Nicola Zaccaria, recognized Venetian suzerainty.<ref>{{cite book|title=Islamic studies|year=1997|publisher=Islamic Research Institute|location=Pakistan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w1DrAAAAMAAJ|author =Central Institute of Islamic Research|accessdate=22 March 2012|page=194|quote=Among those disloyal vassals was Ivan Kastrioti, Niketas Thopia and Nicola Zaccaria.}}</ref> Numerous members of Albanian noble families were Venetian [[Pronoia|pronoiers]].<ref>{{harvnb|Serbian Academy of Science|1980|p=43}}{{quote|\u0420\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0447 \u0425\u0443\u043c\u043e\u0458 \u0431\u0438\u043e \u0458\u0435 \u0432\u0440\u043b\u043e \u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043a\u043d\u0443\u0442\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430\u0440 \u0443 \u0421\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0458\u0443}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Serbian Academy of Science|1980|p=49}}{{quote|\u0420\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0447 \u0425\u0443\u043c\u043e\u0458 \u0458\u0435 \u0443\u043c\u0440\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0435 \u043d\u043e \u0448\u0442\u043e \u0458\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043d \u0441\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0458. \u0411\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0447 \u0458\u0435, \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435 \u045a\u0435\u0433\u0430, \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u043e \u045a\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043c \u0431\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0443 \u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0438\u0458\u0438, \u043a\u043e\u0458\u0438 \u0458\u0435 \u0431\u0438\u043e \u0432\u043e\u0458\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0430 \u0438\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0434 \u0421\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0440\u0430, \u0438 \u0441\u0438\u043d\u0443 \u041a\u043e\u0458\u0447\u0438\u043d\u0443.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Rivista di studi bizantini e neoellenici, Volume 7|year=1953|publisher=Istituto per l'Europa orientale (Rome, Italy), Associazione nazionale per gli studi bizantini|location=Rome|url=https://books.google.com/?id=fnByMULE5aMC&dq=humoj+albania&q=humoj#search_anchor|accessdate=28 January 2012|page=506}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last= Antonovi\u0107 |first=Milo\u0161 |title=Town and district in littoral of Zeta and northern Albania in 14th and 15th century |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KhcUAQAAMAAJ|year=2003 |publisher= Istorijski institut |location= Belgrade |language= Serbian |isbn=9788677430313 |oclc= 55953999 |page=216 |quote=\u041d\u0430\u0438\u043c\u0435, \u0436\u0435\u043d\u0435\u045b\u0438 \u0441\u0435 1433 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435 \u045b\u0435\u0440\u043a\u043e\u043c \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u0421\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0430, \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0447 II \u0425\u0443\u043c\u043e\u0458 \u0458\u0435 \u0434\u043e\u0431\u0438\u043e \u0441\u0435\u043b\u043e \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0459\u0438 \u0443 \u0431\u0430\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0434\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0442\u0443}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Schmitt|2001|p=491}}{{quote|Radic und Maran Humoj verwalteten seit 1441 Gleros bei Skutari, das einst den Bonzi geh\u00f6rt hatte.}}</ref><ref>The Late Medieval Balkans: A Critical Survey from the Late Twelfth Century to the Ottoman Conquest Author John Van Antwerp Fine Edition reprint, illustrated Publisher University of Michigan Press, 1994  {{ISBN|0472082604}}, 9780472082605 p. 510 \"Koja [Zaharia] submitted to Venice\"</ref> Many Albanian noblemen fought against Skanderbeg within Venetian forces during [[Albanian\u2013Venetian War (1447\u20131448)|Albanian\u2013Venetian War]].<ref>{{harvnb|Schmitt|2001|p=490}}{{quote|In einer getreidearmen Gegend war dies ein Anschlag auf die Lebensgrundlagen der Gemeinde. Venedig ging in dieser Frage \u00e4usserst behutsam vor, denn Koja und Andreas Humoj hatten der Signoria bedeutende Dienste geleistet. Zusammen mit Simeon Vulkata waren sie an der Spitze der venezianischen Verb\u00e4nde gegen Skanderbeg ins Feld gezogen (1447). In ihren Machtgebieten um Balezo und Drivasto wurde besonders heftig gek\u00e4mpft.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Zbornik Filozofskog fakulteta, Volume 8|year=1964|publisher=Nau\u010dno delo|location=Belgrade|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M947AQAAIAAJ|author =Univerzitet u Beogradu. Filozofski fakultet|accessdate=28 January 2012|quote= \u041c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u0438 \u0434\u043e\u043c\u0430\u045b\u0438 \u0459\u0443\u0434\u0438 \u0443\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0441\u0443 \u0443 \u0431\u043e\u0440\u0431\u0430\u043c\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u041c\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0430\u0447\u043a\u043e\u0458 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438. \u041a\u043e\u0458\u0430 \u0425\u0443\u043c\u043e\u0458... \u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u0423\u0433\u0440\u0438\u043d,...\u0408\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d \u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430 \u0438 \u045a\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0432 \u0431\u0440\u0430\u0442...\u0441\u0435\u0434\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0446\u0435 \u0431\u0440\u0430\u045b\u0435 \u041f\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0438...\u0432\u0438\u0448\u0435 \u045a\u0438\u0445\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0445 \u0440\u043e\u0452\u0430\u043a\u0430...\u0442\u0440\u0438 \u0441\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0420\u0430\u0458\u043a\u0430 \u041c\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0442\u0435...\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0430\u0440 \u041c\u0430\u043b\u043e\u043d\u0448\u0438 \u0441\u0430 \u0434\u0432\u0430 \u0441\u0438\u043d\u0430...\u0438 \u0411\u0443\u0448\u0430 \u0421\u043e\u0440\u045a\u0430 \u0438\u0437 \u0414\u0430\u045a\u0430...\u0414\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0438\u043c\u0430 \u0438 \u043d\u0435\u043c\u0430 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0433\u0430...|page=419|language=Serbian}}</ref>\n\n== Kingdom of Naples ==\nIn 1451, many Albanian noblemen became vassals of the [[Kingdom of Naples]]. The first was Skanderbeg who signed the [[Treaty of Gaeta]] on March 26, 1451 and after him many other Albanian noblemen like [[Gjergj Arianiti|George Araniti]], Ghin Musachi, George Stresi Balsha, [[Peter Spani (League of Lezh\u00eb)|Peter Spani]], [[Pal Dukagjini]], Thopia Musachi, Peter of Himara, Simon Zanebisha and Carlo Toco signed similar treaties.<ref>{{Citation|last=Noli|first=Fan Stilian|authorlink=Fan Stilian Noli|year=1947|title=George Castrioti Scanderbeg (1405\u20131468)|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=IdhBAAAAIAAJ|publisher=International Universities Press|oclc=732882|page=49|quote= Later on Alphonse concluded similar treaties with George Araniti, Ghin Musachi, George Stresi Balsha, Peter Spani, Paul Ducaghini,... }}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=Setton |first=Kenneth  |authorlink= Kenneth Setton |title=The Papacy and the Levant, 1204\u20131571 |volume= 4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0Sz2VYI0l1IC&pg=PA102|year= 1976\u20131984 |publisher= American Philosophical Society |isbn=978-0-87169-114-9 |pages=102, 103 |quote= Scanderbeg now entered into special close relations with King Alphoso of Naples....on 26 March 1451. They got along very well together, as lord and vassal...Besides Alphonso's assertion of suzerainty over Skanderbeg and the latters father in law George Arianiti Topia Golem Cominovi\u0107,... Alphonso gave recognition as vassals to Ducagjini family, to Simon Zenevisi, ...  }}</ref> Skanderbeg had to fulfill his vassal obligations to [[Skanderbeg's Italian expedition|send his forces to Italy]] to support [[Ferdinand I of Naples]] in his struggle against the [[House of Valois-Anjou|Angevin Dynasty]].<ref>{{Citation |last=Elsie |first=Robert |authorlink= Robert Elsie |title= Historical dictionary of Albania |year=2010 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |location=Lanham  |isbn=978-0-8108-7380-3 |oclc=454375231 |page=367 |chapter= Independent Albania (1912\u20141944) |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=haFlGXIg8uoC&pg=PA503|quote= In 1458, Scanderbeg was summoned to Italy to fulfil his obligations as vassal under the treaty of Gaeta.}}</ref> In return, the Kingdom of Naples provided financial and military support to its vassals in Albania and maintained a permanent garrison in Kruje.<ref>{{cite book|title=The New Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|year=1987|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|url=https://books.google.com/?id=YaRXAAAAMAAJ&dq=skanderbeg+vassal+alfonso&q=%22Skanderbeg+in+1451+made+an+alliance+with+King+Alfonso+I+of+Naples+%28Alfonso+V+of+Aragon%29%2C+whose+vassal+he+became%2C+and+a+permanent+Neapolitan+garrison+was+installed+in+his+fortress%22#search_anchor|accessdate=26 March 2012|page=213|quote=Skanderbeg in 1451 made an alliance with King Alfonso I of Naples (Alfonso V of Aragon), whose vassal he became, and a permanent Neapolitan garrison was installed in his fortress|isbn=9780852294437}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Spomenik, Volumes 95-97|year=1942|publisher=Serbian Academy of Science and Arts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E-fTAAAAMAAJ|page=xvi|language=Serbian|quote=\u041a\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043b \u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438 \u043a\u043e\u0434 \u041d\u0430\u043f\u0443\u0459\u0430, 21. \u043e\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0431\u0430\u0440 1454: \u041a\u0440\u0430\u0459 \u0410\u043b\u0444\u043e\u043d\u0441 V \u0458\u0430\u0432\u0459\u0430 \u0421\u043a\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0435\u0433\u0443 \u0434\u0430 \u043c\u0443 \u0458\u0435 \u041f\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435 \u0414\u0443\u043a\u0430\u0452\u0438\u043d\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0433 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0438\u0437\u0458\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043e \u043e\u0434\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u0438 \u043f\u043e\u043a\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u0438 \u0434\u0430 \u043c\u0443 \u0458\u0435 \u043a\u0430\u043e \u0441\u0432\u043e\u043c \u0432\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0443, \u043e\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043e \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0448\u045a\u0443 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0437\u0438\u0458\u0443 \u043e\u0434 300 \u0434\u0443\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430 ...}}</ref>\n\n== Religion and language ==\nThe [[religion]] of the Albanian nobility depended on the religion of their lords, or the power that could threaten their political existence.<ref>{{cite book|title=Bulgarian historical review|year=2003|publisher=Pub. House of the Bulgarian Academy of Sciences|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lD5pAAAAMAAJ|page=177|quote=The Albanian nobility embraced the religion of their lord or of that power which could threaten its political existence.}}</ref> Until the end of 14th century the Albanian nobility were [[Christians]] (Orthodox or Catholic). After the [[Battle of Savra]] in 1385 most of the local Albanian nobility became vassals of the Ottoman Empire<ref>Sedlar, Jean W. ''East Central Europe in the Middle Ages, 1000\u20131500,'' University of Washington Press, p. 385</ref> and began converting to Islam. In the end of 17th century the Albanian nobility was majority [[islamized]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Islamic studies|year=1997|publisher=Islamic Research Institute|location=Pakistan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w1DrAAAAMAAJ|author =Central Institute of Islamic Research|accessdate=16 March 2012|page=196|quote=The Albanian nobility and townfolk from Kosovo were totally Islamized in the end of the 17th century.}}</ref>\n\nThe official language of correspondence in the [[Albanian principalities|Medieval principalities in Albania]] controlled by local nobility were [[Greek language|Greek]], [[Latin language|Latin]] or [[Slavic languages|Slavic]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Bulgarian historical review|year=2003|publisher=Pub. House of the Bulgarian Academy of Sciences|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lD5pAAAAMAAJ|page=164|quote=Local principalities... using Greek, Ladin or Slavic as the official languages of correspondence in their courts.}}</ref>\n\n== Restoration ==\nAn attempt to restore the [[monarchy]] in 1997 was rejected by about two-thirds of those voting in a [[Albanian monarchy referendum, 1997|referendum]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/2072440.stm Ex-king's son returns to Albania], ''[[BBC News Online]]'', 28 June 2002.</ref> Former noble families and their descendants are still a part of society in Albania, but they no longer retain any specific privileges.\n\n== Noble families ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Alltuni family]]\n* [[Arianiti family]]\n* [[Bal\u0161i\u0107 noble family|Balshaj family]]\n* [[Blinishti family]]\n* [[:Category:Bua family|Bua]]/[[Shpata family]]\n* [[Bushati family]]\n* [[Dukagjini family]]\n* [[Dushmani family]]\n* [[Gropa family]]\n* [[Humoj family]]\n* [[Jonima family]]\n* [[Losha family]]\n* [[Kastrioti family]]\n* [[K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc family|Qypryli (K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc) family]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Military history|year=1990|publisher=Empire Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ED1WAAAAYAAJ|page=49|quote=The Kuprilis, Albanian noblemen,}}</ref>\n* [[Mataranga family]]\n* [[Muzaka family]]\n* [[Progon family]]\n* [[Shira family]]\n* [[Spani family]]\n* [[Taushani family]]\n* [[Thopia family]]\n* [[Vrioni family]]\n* [[Zaharia family]]\n* [[Zenebishi Family]]\n* [[House of Zogu|Zogu family]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{Citation |author= Serbian Academy of Science |title=Glas, Volumes 319\u2013323|year=1980|publisher=Serbian Academy of Science and Arts|location=Belgrade|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kqorAQAAIAAJ|language=Serbian|ref=harv}}\n* {{Citation |last=Schmitt |first=Oliver Jens |authorlink=Oliver Jens Schmitt |title=Das venezianische Albanien (1392\u20131479) |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eKKS3u7iPWcC&pg=PA490|year=2001 |publisher=R. Oldenbourg Verlag GmbH M\u00fcnchen |location= M\u00fcnchen|isbn=3-486-56569-9 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{Albania topics}}\n{{European nobility}}\n{{Nobility by nation}}\n\n[[Category:Albanian nobility| ]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Albanian nobility''' was an [[elite]] hereditary ruling class in [[Albania]], parts of the western [[Balkans]] and later in parts of the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] world. The Albanian nobility was composed of landowners of vast areas, often in allegiance to states like the [[Byzantine Empire]], various [[Serbia in the Middle Ages|Serbian states]], the [[Republic of Venice]], the [[Ottoman Empire]] and the [[Kingdom of Naples]] in addition to the [[Albanian principalities]]. They often used Byzantine, Latin or Slavic titles,<ref>{{cite book|title=Bulgarian historical review|year=2003|publisher=Pub. House of the Bulgarian Academy of Sciences|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lD5pAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Albanian+nobility%22&dq=%22Albanian+nobility%22|accessdate=16 March 2012|page=164|quote=Albanian nobility used intensively a titulature* of Byzantine, Latin or Slavic origins}}</ref> such as [[sebastokrator]], [[Despot (court title)|despot]], [[dux]], [[Count|conte]] and [[\u017dupan|zupan]].\n\n== Byzantine Empire ==\n{{Further|Albania under the Byzantine Empire}}\nThe [[Muzaka family]] was loyal to the [[Byzantine Empire]]. For their loyalty to Byzantium, the head of the family [[Andrea II Muzaka]] gained the title of [[Despot (court title)|Despot]] in 1335, while other Muzakas continued to pursue careers in Byzantine administration in Constantinople.<ref name=Anamalipp252-255>{{citation|last=Anamali|first=Sk\u00ebnder|title=Historia e popullit shqiptar n\u00eb kat\u00ebr v\u00ebllime|volume=I|year=2002|page=252|publisher=Botimet Toena|language=Albanian|oclc=52411919}}</ref>\n\n== Principality of Arbanon ==\n{{main|Principality of Arbanon}}\nThe first Albanian state in the Middle Ages it was ruled by the [[Progon family|Progoni family]] and extended from the [[Drin (river)|Drin]] river to the southern boundary of the [[Lake Ohrid|Ohrid lake]]. Its rulers were known in Catholic sources with the titles of judices, while in Byzantine ones the titles mentioned are those of the grand [[archon]] and the [[panhypersebastos]].\n\n== Kingdom of Serbia ==\nWhen [[Durr\u00ebs]] was captured by the [[Kingdom of Serbia (medieval)|Kingdom of Serbia]], [[Stephen Uro\u0161 II Milutin of Serbia|Milutin]] was titled the King of Albania while his rule was occasionally recognized by Albanian noblemen around Durr\u00ebs.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Rad Jugoslavenske akademije znanosti i umjetnosti]]|issue=257|year=1937|publisher=Yugoslav Academy of Sciences and Arts|url=https://books.google.com/?id=i9wVAQAAIAAJ&dq=%D0%B4%D1%80%D0%B0%D1%87+%D0%BA%D1%80%D0%B0%D1%99+%D0%BC%D0%B8%D0%BB%D1%83%D1%82%D0%B8%D0%BD&q=%22Kasnije%2C+kad+je+Dra%C4%8D+pao+u+srpske+ruke%2C+nosi%C4%87e+kralj+Milutin+naslov+kralja+Arbanije.%22#search_anchor|accessdate=22 March 2012|page=259|language=Serbian|quote=Kasnije, kad je Dra\u010d pao u srpske ruke, nosi\u0107e kralj Milutin naslov kralja Arbanije.|title=Rad Jugoslavenske akademije znanosti i umjetnosti}}{{title missing|date=June 2016}}{{author missing|date=June 2016}}</ref> Many Albanian noblemen were included in the feudal hierarchy of the Kingdom of Serbia and had titles and privileges of \u017eupans, voivodas or [[kaznac]]s.<ref>{{cite book| last= Bogdanovi\u0107| first= Dimitrije| authorlink = Dimitrije Bogdanovi\u0107| editor= Antonije Isakovi\u0107| title= Knjiga o Kosovu| url = http://www.kosovo.net/sk/rastko-kosovo/istorija/knjiga_o_kosovu/index.html| accessdate    = January 9, 2011| volume    = 2| origyear  = 1984|date=November 2000| publisher = [[Serbian Academy of Sciences and Arts]]| location  = Belgrade| language  = Serbian| chapter   = Albanski pokreti 1908-1912.|trans-chapter=| chapterurl= http://www.kosovo.net/sk/rastko-kosovo/istorija/knjiga_o_kosovu/bogdanovic-kosovo_2.html| quote=  srpskog kralja Milutina [1282-1321]... vlast srpskog kralja priznavali su povremeno i albanski velika\u0161i u zale\u0111u Dra\u010da...Jo\u0161 u doba kralja Milutina albanski feudalci ce uklju\u010duju u feudalni poredak srpske dr\u017eave sa zvanjima i beneficijama \u017eupana, vojvode ili kaznaca.}}</ref>\n\n== Serbian Empire ==\n{{Further|Albania under the Serbian Empire}}\nAlbanian nobility was included into hierarchy of the feudal system of [[Serbian Empire]] without any discrimination and participated in the work of the highest government institutions, where Albanian [[archons]] had the same rights as the [[Serbian nobility]] had.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bogdanovi\u0107|first=Dimitrije| authorlink = Dimitrije Bogdanovi\u0107| editor=Antonije Isakovi\u0107|title=Knjiga o Kosovu| url = http://www.kosovo.net/sk/rastko-kosovo/istorija/knjiga_o_kosovu/index.html| accessdate    = January 9, 2011| volume    = 2| origyear  = 1984|date=November 2000| publisher = [[Serbian Academy of Sciences and Arts]]| location  = Belgrade| language  = Serbian| chapter   = Albanski pokreti 1908-1912.|trans-chapter=| chapterurl= http://www.kosovo.net/sk/rastko-kosovo/istorija/knjiga_o_kosovu/bogdanovic-kosovo_2.html| quote=  U Du\u0161anovom carstvu albanske zemlje i velika\u0161i Albanije obuhva\u0107eni su bez ikakvog izdvajanja i diskriminacije hijerarhijskim feudalnim sistemom....Politi\u010dka integracija Albanaca u srednjovekovnoj srpskoj dr\u017eavi izvr\u0161ena je u okviru feudalnog sistema bez diskriminacije prema albanskoj vlasteli. Sa svojim starim ili novim zvanjima, ste\u010denim ili tek dobijenim povlasticama, sa ba\u0161tinama, pronijama i drugim feudalnim pravima albanski feudalci, u meri u kojoj su ulazili u srpsku dr\u017eavu, bili su aktivan \u010dinilac te dr\u017eave. U titulama srpskih kraljeva odnosno careva, kao \u0161to smo videli, albanski narod je do\u0161ao i do svojevrsnog dr\u017eavnopravnog legitimiteta. Ovaj ce legitimitet izra\u017eavao i u pravima albanske vlastele da u\u010destvuje u radu najvi\u0161ih organa vlasti srpske dr\u017eave, srpskih sabora. Ve\u0107 sa \u0161irenjem granica srpske dr\u017eave preko gr\u010dkih i albanskih oblasti, kako je primetio Nikola Radoj\u010di\u0107, javilo ce pitanje o u\u010destvovanju Grka i Albanaca na srpskim saborima; gr\u010dki i albanski arhonti su i u\u010destvovali u radu sabora sa svim pravima srpske vlastele. }}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Uq0rAQAAIAAJ&q=%D0%B0%D0%BB%D0%B1%D0%B0%D0%BD%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B8+%D1%81%D1%82%D0%B5%D1%84%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B0+%D0%B4%D1%83%D1%88%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B0+%D0%B2%D0%BB%D0%B0%D1%81%D1%82%D0%B5%D0%BB%D0%B0&dq=%D0%B0%D0%BB%D0%B1%D0%B0%D0%BD%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B8+%D1%81%D1%82%D0%B5%D1%84%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B0+%D0%B4%D1%83%D1%88%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B0+%D0%B2%D0%BB%D0%B0%D1%81%D1%82%D0%B5%D0%BB%D0%B0&hl=sr&sa=X&ei=D1xqT7OBFsTCswakzPnCAg&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAg \u0423 \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435 \u0458\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0433 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440\u0430 \u0441\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0435 \u0434\u0440\u0436\u0430\u0432\u0435 \u0443 \u0441\u0440\u0435\u0434\u045a\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0443 \u0410\u043b- \u0431\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0443 \u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0442\u043f\u0443\u043d\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0432\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0446\u0430\u0440\u0430 \u0421\u0442\u0435\u0444\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u0414\u0443\u0448\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u0430\u0440\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0448\u043a\u0430 \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0458\u0435 \u0430\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043d \u0438 \u0432\u0440\u043b\u043e \u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u0458\u0430\u043d \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u0447\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043b\u0430\u0446 \u0443 \u0437\u0435\u043c\u0459\u0438.], p.42 - Glas, \u0422\u043e\u043c 338, Srpska akademija nauka i umetnosti, 1983</ref> [[Stephen Uro\u0161 IV Du\u0161an of Serbia|Serbian emperor]] wanted to gain the support of the Albanian nobility so he confirmed the privileges Kruje had been granted by the [[Byzantine Empire]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Christos Soulis|first=George|title=The Serbs and Byzantium during the reign of Tsar Stephen Du\u0161an (1331-1355) and his successors|year=1984|url=https://books.google.com/?id=NXFpAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Albanian+nobility%22&dq=%22Albanian+nobility%22|accessdate=26 March 2012|page=136|quote=The chrysobull that Dusan issued in June 13h3, by which he confirmed the privileges of Kroja that had been granted by the Byzantine emperors, clearly indicates that the Serbian ruler sought to win the support of the Albanian nobility. From the evidence of this document we may assume that Du\u0161an entrusted to the local nobility the administration of various Albanian cities|isbn=9780884021377}}</ref>\n\n== Ottoman Empire ==\n{{Further|History of Albania during Ottoman administration}}\nA decisive point of the relation of Albanian nobility with Ottoman Empire was the [[Battle of Savra]] in 1385.<ref>{{cite book|title=Studia Albanica, Volume 38, Issue 1|year=2005|publisher=Acad\u00e9mie des sciences de la R\u00e9publique Populaire d'Albanie, Institut d'histoire, Institut de linguistique et litt\u00e9rature.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=y4RpAAAAMAAJ&dq=Battle+of+Savra+1385+ottoman+vassal&q=%22+the+first+contacts+between+the+Albanian+nobility+and+the+Ottomans+was+the+Battle+of+Savra+%28ca.+1385%29.%22#search_anchor|authors =Universiteti Shtet\u00ebror i Tiran\u00ebs. Instituti i Historis\u00eb e Gjuh\u00ebsis\u00eb, Instituti i Gjuh\u00ebsis\u00eb dhe i Let\u00ebrsis\u00eb (Akademia e Shkencave e RPS t\u00eb Shqip\u00ebris\u00eb), Akademia e Shkencave e RPSH. Instituti i Ghuh\u00ebsis\u00eb dhe i Let\u00ebrsis\u00eb, Instituti i Historis\u00eb (Akademia e Shkencave e RPS t\u00eb Shqip\u00ebris\u00eb)|accessdate=26 March 2012|page=85|quote=A turning point in the first contacts between the Albanian nobility and the Ottomans was the Battle of Savra (ca. 1385).}}</ref> After the Battle of Savra Albanian nobility became vassals of the Ottoman Empire.<ref>{{cite book|title=Studia Albanica, Volume 38, Issue 1|year=2005|publisher=Acad\u00e9mie des sciences de la R\u00e9publique Populaire d'Albanie, Institut d'histoire, Institut de linguistique et litt\u00e9rature.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=y4RpAAAAMAAJ&dq=Battle+of+Savra+1385+ottoman+vassal&q=%22After+the+Battle+of+Savra+Albanian+princes+became+vassals+of+the+Ottomans.%22#search_anchor|authors =Universiteti Shtet\u00ebror i Tiran\u00ebs. Instituti i Historis\u00eb e Gjuh\u00ebsis\u00eb, Instituti i Gjuh\u00ebsis\u00eb dhe i Let\u00ebrsis\u00eb (Akademia e Shkencave e RPS t\u00eb Shqip\u00ebris\u00eb), Akademia e Shkencave e RPSH. Instituti i Ghuh\u00ebsis\u00eb dhe i Let\u00ebrsis\u00eb, Instituti i Historis\u00eb (Akademia e Shkencave e RPS t\u00eb Shqip\u00ebris\u00eb)|accessdate=26 March 2012|page=85|quote=After the Battle of Savra Albanian princes became vassals of the Ottomans.}}</ref>\n\nAlbanian nobility did not fight against Ottomans with united and compact forces like Serbian and Bulgarian aristocracy, but with small independent local rulers.<ref>{{cite book|last=Skendi|first=Stavro|title=Balkan cultural studies|year=1980|publisher=East European Monographs|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JWBiAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Albanian+nobility%22&dq=%22Albanian+nobility%22|accessdate=26 March 2012|page=172|quote=...the Bulgarian and Serbian aristocracies...In the first place, the Albanian feudal lords did not fight against the Ottomans, as the Bulgarians and Serbs in an orderly battle, with united and compact forces.|isbn=9780914710660}}</ref> Therefore, the Ottomans, who have been since claimed to be \"brutal and cruel\" to the Serbian and Bulgarian nobility, might have been conciliatory with the Albanian nobility.<ref>{{cite book|last=Skendi|first=Stavro|title=Balkan cultural studies|year=1980|publisher=East European Monographs|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JWBiAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Albanian+nobility%22&dq=%22Albanian+nobility%22|accessdate=26 March 2012|page=172|quote=One might wonder why the Ottomans, who were so harsh on the Bulgarian and Serbian aristocracies, were so conciliatory with the Albanian nobility.|isbn=9780914710660}}</ref>\n\nWhen Albania became part of the [[Ottoman Empire]], it was divided into [[sanjaks]] with numerous [[timars]]. Many members of the Albanian nobility held high rank positions within Ottoman the hierarchy, like [[Skanderbeg]] and [[Ballaban Badera]] who were Ottoman sanjakbeys.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omda.bg/imir/studies/alban_id9.html |title=Albanian identities |first=Antonina |last=Zhelyazkova |date= |publisher= |location= |page= |pages= |at= |trans-title= |doi= |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.omda.bg%2Fimir%2Fstudies%2Falban_id9.html&date=2011-04-03 |archivedate=April 3, 2011 |accessdate=April 3, 2011 |quote=In 1440, he was promoted to sancakbey of Debar |ref= |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=\u0130nalc\u0131k  |first=Halil |authorlink=Halil \u0130nalc\u0131k |title=From empire to republic : essays on Ottoman and Turkish social history |url=https://books.google.com/?id=kIhpAAAAMAAJ&q=balaban+ohrid&dq=balaban+ohrid  |accessdate= 4 January 2012 |edition= |series= |publisher=  Isis Press |location= Istanbul |isbn=9789754280807 |oclc=34985150 |page=88 |quote=Balaban Aga, qui a accord\u00e9 des timar \u00e0 ses propres soldats dans la Basse- Dibra et dans la \u00c7ermeni\u00e7a, ainsi qu'\u00e0 son neveu \u00e0 Mati, doit \u00eatre ce m\u00eame Balaban Aga, sancakbeyi d'Ohrid, connu pour ses batailles sanglantes contre Skanderbeg. |year=1995 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Balkans: a short history from Greek times to the present day, Volume 1972, Part 2 |last=H\u00f6sch |first=Peter |year=1972 |publisher=Crane, Russak |location= |isbn= 978-0-8448-0072-1 |page=96 |url= https://books.google.com/?id=2RoXAQAAIAAJ&q=sanjak+of+dibra&dq=sanjak+of+dibra|accessdate= April 4, 2011}}</ref> Some members of the Albanian nobility were Ottoman [[timariots]].<ref>{{cite book|title=AARP, art and archaeology research papers|year=1975|url=https://books.google.com/?id=IXVXAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Albanian+nobility%22+turkish+language&q=%22Some+timars+were+acquired+by+members+of+the+Albanian+nobility%2C+while+others+were+held+by+members+of+the+Turkish+military+class%2C%22#search_anchor|accessdate=16 March 2012|page=61|quote=Some timars were acquired by members of the Albanian nobility,}}</ref> Through the implementation of the [[Timar#Timar system|timar system]] the Albanian nobility was absorbed into the Ottoman military class within not more than two generations.<ref>{{Citation |last=Schmitt |first=Oliver Jens|editor= |others= |title=Religion und Kultur im albanischsprachigen S\u00fcdosteuropa |url= https://books.google.com/?id=aCdYHU9PtiIC&pg=PA20&dq=albanian+nobility#v=onepage&q=albanian%20nobility&f=false |volume= 4 |year=2010 |publisher= Lang |location=Frankfurt am Main, Berlin, Bern, Bruxelles, New York, Oxford, Wien |isbn= 978-3-631-60295-9 |page=22|quote= After the adoption of timar system, the absorption of Albanian nobility into Ottoman military class did not take more than two generations }}</ref> They adopted the [[List of Ottoman titles and appellations|Ottoman titles]] like [[Agha (Ottoman Empire)|aga]], [[bey]] or [[Pashas|pasha]].\n\n== Venetian Republic ==\n{{Further|Venetian Albania}}\n\nDuring the period of crisis for the Ottoman Empire after the [[Battle of Ankara]] in 1402 several Ottoman vassals from Albania including  [[Gjon Kastrioti]], Niketas Thopia and Nicola Zaccaria, recognized Venetian suzerainty.<ref>{{cite book|title=Islamic studies|year=1997|publisher=Islamic Research Institute|location=Pakistan|url=https://books.google.com/?id=w1DrAAAAMAAJ&q=albanian+vassals&dq=albanian+vassals|author =Central Institute of Islamic Research|accessdate=22 March 2012|page=194|quote=Among those disloyal vassals was Ivan Kastrioti, Niketas Thopia and Nicola Zaccaria.}}</ref> Numerous members of Albanian noble families were Venetian [[Pronoia|pronoiers]].<ref>{{harvnb|Serbian Academy of Science|1980|p=43}}{{quote|\u0420\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0447 \u0425\u0443\u043c\u043e\u0458 \u0431\u0438\u043e \u0458\u0435 \u0432\u0440\u043b\u043e \u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043a\u043d\u0443\u0442\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430\u0440 \u0443 \u0421\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0458\u0443}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Serbian Academy of Science|1980|p=49}}{{quote|\u0420\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0447 \u0425\u0443\u043c\u043e\u0458 \u0458\u0435 \u0443\u043c\u0440\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0435 \u043d\u043e \u0448\u0442\u043e \u0458\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043d \u0441\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0458. \u0411\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0447 \u0458\u0435, \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435 \u045a\u0435\u0433\u0430, \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043f\u0430\u043e \u045a\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043c \u0431\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0443 \u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0438\u0458\u0438, \u043a\u043e\u0458\u0438 \u0458\u0435 \u0431\u0438\u043e \u0432\u043e\u0458\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0430 \u0438\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0434 \u0421\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0440\u0430, \u0438 \u0441\u0438\u043d\u0443 \u041a\u043e\u0458\u0447\u0438\u043d\u0443.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Rivista di studi bizantini e neoellenici, Volume 7|year=1953|publisher=Istituto per l'Europa orientale (Rome, Italy), Associazione nazionale per gli studi bizantini|location=Rome|url=https://books.google.com/?id=fnByMULE5aMC&dq=humoj+albania&q=humoj#search_anchor|accessdate=28 January 2012|page=506}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last= Antonovi\u0107 |first=Milo\u0161 |title=Town and district in littoral of Zeta and northern Albania in 14th and 15th century |url=https://books.google.com/?id=KhcUAQAAMAAJ&dq=%22%D0%BF%D0%B5%D1%82%D0%B0%D1%80+%D1%81%D0%BF%D0%B0%D0%BD%22&q=%D1%81%D0%BF%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B0#search_anchor |year=2003 |publisher= Istorijski institut |location= Belgrade |language= Serbian |isbn=9788677430313 |oclc= 55953999 |page=216 |quote=\u041d\u0430\u0438\u043c\u0435, \u0436\u0435\u043d\u0435\u045b\u0438 \u0441\u0435 1433 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435 \u045b\u0435\u0440\u043a\u043e\u043c \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u0421\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0430, \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0447 II \u0425\u0443\u043c\u043e\u0458 \u0458\u0435 \u0434\u043e\u0431\u0438\u043e \u0441\u0435\u043b\u043e \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0459\u0438 \u0443 \u0431\u0430\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0434\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0442\u0443}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Schmitt|2001|p=491}}{{quote|Radic und Maran Humoj verwalteten seit 1441 Gleros bei Skutari, das einst den Bonzi geh\u00f6rt hatte.}}</ref><ref>The Late Medieval Balkans: A Critical Survey from the Late Twelfth Century to the Ottoman Conquest Author John Van Antwerp Fine Edition reprint, illustrated Publisher University of Michigan Press, 1994  {{ISBN|0472082604}}, 9780472082605 p. 510 \"Koja [Zaharia] submitted to Venice\"</ref> Many Albanian noblemen fought against Skanderbeg within Venetian forces during [[Albanian\u2013Venetian War (1447\u20131448)|Albanian\u2013Venetian War]].<ref>{{harvnb|Schmitt|2001|p=490}}{{quote|In einer getreidearmen Gegend war dies ein Anschlag auf die Lebensgrundlagen der Gemeinde. Venedig ging in dieser Frage \u00e4usserst behutsam vor, denn Koja und Andreas Humoj hatten der Signoria bedeutende Dienste geleistet. Zusammen mit Simeon Vulkata waren sie an der Spitze der venezianischen Verb\u00e4nde gegen Skanderbeg ins Feld gezogen (1447). In ihren Machtgebieten um Balezo und Drivasto wurde besonders heftig gek\u00e4mpft.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Zbornik Filozofskog fakulteta, Volume 8|year=1964|publisher=Nau\u010dno delo|location=Belgrade|url=https://books.google.com/?id=M947AQAAIAAJ&dq=%D0%A5%D1%83%D0%BC%D0%BE%D1%98+%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B4%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B1%D0%B5%D0%B3&q=%22%D0%9A%D0%BE%D1%98%D0%B0+%D0%A5%D1%83%D0%BC%D0%BE%D1%98%22#search_anchor|author =Univerzitet u Beogradu. Filozofski fakultet|accessdate=28 January 2012|quote= \u041c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u0438 \u0434\u043e\u043c\u0430\u045b\u0438 \u0459\u0443\u0434\u0438 \u0443\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0441\u0443 \u0443 \u0431\u043e\u0440\u0431\u0430\u043c\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u041c\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0430\u0447\u043a\u043e\u0458 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438. \u041a\u043e\u0458\u0430 \u0425\u0443\u043c\u043e\u0458... \u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u0423\u0433\u0440\u0438\u043d,...\u0408\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d \u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430 \u0438 \u045a\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0432 \u0431\u0440\u0430\u0442...\u0441\u0435\u0434\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0446\u0435 \u0431\u0440\u0430\u045b\u0435 \u041f\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0438...\u0432\u0438\u0448\u0435 \u045a\u0438\u0445\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0445 \u0440\u043e\u0452\u0430\u043a\u0430...\u0442\u0440\u0438 \u0441\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0420\u0430\u0458\u043a\u0430 \u041c\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0442\u0435...\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0430\u0440 \u041c\u0430\u043b\u043e\u043d\u0448\u0438 \u0441\u0430 \u0434\u0432\u0430 \u0441\u0438\u043d\u0430...\u0438 \u0411\u0443\u0448\u0430 \u0421\u043e\u0440\u045a\u0430 \u0438\u0437 \u0414\u0430\u045a\u0430...\u0414\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0438\u043c\u0430 \u0438 \u043d\u0435\u043c\u0430 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0433\u0430...|page=419|language=Serbian}}</ref>\n\n== Kingdom of Naples ==\nIn 1451, many Albanian noblemen became vassals of the [[Kingdom of Naples]]. The first was Skanderbeg who signed the [[Treaty of Gaeta]] on March 26, 1451 and after him many other Albanian noblemen like [[Gjergj Arianiti|George Araniti]], Ghin Musachi, George Stresi Balsha, [[Peter Spani (League of Lezh\u00eb)|Peter Spani]], [[Pal Dukagjini]], Thopia Musachi, Peter of Himara, Simon Zanebisha and Carlo Toco signed similar treaties.<ref>{{Citation|last=Noli|first=Fan Stilian|authorlink=Fan Stilian Noli|year=1947|title=George Castrioti Scanderbeg (1405\u20131468)|url= https://books.google.com/?id=IdhBAAAAIAAJ&q=%22peter+spani%22&dq=%22peter+spani%22 |publisher=International Universities Press|oclc=732882|page=49|quote= Later on Alphonse concluded similar treaties with George Araniti, Ghin Musachi, George Stresi Balsha, Peter Spani, Paul Ducaghini,... }}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=Setton |first=Kenneth  |authorlink= Kenneth Setton |title=The Papacy and the Levant, 1204-1571 |volume= 4 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=0Sz2VYI0l1IC&pg=PA102&dq=noli+skanderbeg+vassal+alfonso#v=onepage&q&f=false |year= 1976\u20131984 |publisher= American Philosophical Society |isbn=978-0-87169-114-9 |pages=102, 103 |quote= Scanderbeg now entered into special close relations with King Alphoso of Naples....on 26 March 1451. They got along very well together, as lord and vassal...Besides Alphonso's assertion of suzerainty over Skanderbeg and the latters father in law George Arianiti Topia Golem Cominovi\u0107,... Alphonso gave recognition as vassals to Ducagjini family, to Simon Zenevisi, ...  }}</ref> Skanderbeg had to fulfill his vassal obligations to [[Skanderbeg's Italian expedition|send his forces to Italy]] to support [[Ferdinand I of Naples]] in his struggle against the [[House of Valois-Anjou|Angevin Dynasty]].<ref>{{Citation |last=Elsie |first=Robert |authorlink= Robert Elsie |title= Historical dictionary of Albania |year=2010 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |location=Lanham  |isbn=978-0-8108-7380-3 |oclc=454375231 |page=367 |chapter= Independent Albania (1912\u20141944) |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=haFlGXIg8uoC&pg=PA503&dq=bey+vlora+%22head+of+state%22+1912+albania&hl=en&sa=X&ei=LJk5T5qILaWB4gTpspShCw&redir_esc=y#v=snippet&q=%22%20Ismail%20Qemal%20Bey%20Vlora%2C%20who%20declared%20Albanian%20independence%20in%201912%2C%20was%20the%20first%20acting%20head%20of%20state%20and%20therefore%20might%20be%20regarded%20as%20the%20country's%20first%20president.%22%20&f=false |quote= In 1458, Scanderbeg was summoned to Italy to fulfil his obligations as vassal under the treaty of Gaeta.}}</ref> In return, the Kingdom of Naples provided financial and military support to its vassals in Albania and maintained a permanent garrison in Kruje.<ref>{{cite book|title=The New Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|year=1987|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|url=https://books.google.com/?id=YaRXAAAAMAAJ&dq=skanderbeg+vassal+alfonso&q=%22Skanderbeg+in+1451+made+an+alliance+with+King+Alfonso+I+of+Naples+%28Alfonso+V+of+Aragon%29%2C+whose+vassal+he+became%2C+and+a+permanent+Neapolitan+garrison+was+installed+in+his+fortress%22#search_anchor|accessdate=26 March 2012|page=213|quote=Skanderbeg in 1451 made an alliance with King Alfonso I of Naples (Alfonso V of Aragon), whose vassal he became, and a permanent Neapolitan garrison was installed in his fortress|isbn=9780852294437}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Spomenik, Volumes 95-97|year=1942|publisher=Serbian Academy of Science and Arts|url=https://books.google.com/?id=E-fTAAAAMAAJ&dq=%D0%B4%D1%83%D1%88%D0%BC%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B8+%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B4%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B1%D0%B5%D0%B3&q=%22%D0%9F%D0%B0%D0%BF%D0%B0+%D0%9D%D0%B8%D0%BA%D0%BE%D0%BB%D0%B0+V+%D1%88%D0%B0%D0%BB%C2%BB%D0%B5+%D0%B8%D0%B7+%D0%A0%D0%B8%D0%BC%D0%B0+%D0%9F%D0%B0%D0%B2%D0%BB%D0%B0+%D0%94%D1%83%D1%88%D0%BC%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B0%2C+%D0%B1%D0%B8%D1%81%D0%BA%D1%83%D0%BF%D0%B0+%D1%83+%D0%94%D1%80%D0%B8%D0%B2%D0%B0%D1%81%D1%82%D1%83%2C+%D0%B4%D0%B0+%D0%B8%D0%B7%D1%80%D0%B0%D0%B2%D0%BD%D0%B0+%D1%81%D0%BF%D0%BE%D1%80+%D0%B8%D0%B7-+Mehj+%D0%A1%D0%BA%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B4%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B1%D0%B5%D0%B3%D0%B0+%D0%B8+%D0%94%D1%83%D0%BA%D0%B0%D0%AC%D0%B8%D0%BD%D0%B0.%22#search_anchor|accessdate=2 February 2012|page=xvi|language=Serbian|quote=\u041a\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043b \u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438 \u043a\u043e\u0434 \u041d\u0430\u043f\u0443\u0459\u0430, 21. \u043e\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0431\u0430\u0440 1454: \u041a\u0440\u0430\u0459 \u0410\u043b\u0444\u043e\u043d\u0441 V \u0458\u0430\u0432\u0459\u0430 \u0421\u043a\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0435\u0433\u0443 \u0434\u0430 \u043c\u0443 \u0458\u0435 \u041f\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435 \u0414\u0443\u043a\u0430\u0452\u0438\u043d\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0433 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0438\u0437\u0458\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043e \u043e\u0434\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u0438 \u043f\u043e\u043a\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u0438 \u0434\u0430 \u043c\u0443 \u0458\u0435 \u043a\u0430\u043e \u0441\u0432\u043e\u043c \u0432\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0443, \u043e\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043e \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0448\u045a\u0443 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0437\u0438\u0458\u0443 \u043e\u0434 300 \u0434\u0443\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430 ...}}</ref>\n\n== Religion and language ==\nThe [[religion]] of the Albanian nobility depended on the religion of their lords, or the power that could threaten their political existence.<ref>{{cite book|title=Bulgarian historical review|year=2003|publisher=Pub. House of the Bulgarian Academy of Sciences|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lD5pAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Albanian+nobility%22&dq=%22Albanian+nobility%22|accessdate=16 March 2012|page=177|quote=The Albanian nobility embraced the religion of their lord or of that power which could threaten its political existence.}}</ref> Until the end of 14th century the Albanian nobility were [[Christians]] (Orthodox or Catholic). After the [[Battle of Savra]] in 1385 most of the local Albanian nobility became vassals of the Ottoman Empire<ref>Sedlar, Jean W. ''East Central Europe in the Middle Ages, 1000-1500,'' University of Washington Press, p. 385</ref> and began converting to Islam. In the end of 17th century the Albanian nobility was majority [[islamized]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Islamic studies|year=1997|publisher=Islamic Research Institute|location=Pakistan|url=https://books.google.com/?id=w1DrAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Albanian+nobility%22+turkish+language&dq=%22Albanian+nobility%22+turkish+language|author =Central Institute of Islamic Research|accessdate=16 March 2012|page=196|quote=The Albanian nobility and townfolk from Kosovo were totally Islamized in the end of the 17th century.}}</ref>\n\nThe official language of correspondence in the [[Albanian principalities|Medieval principalities in Albania]] controlled by local nobility were [[Greek language|Greek]], [[Latin language|Latin]] or [[Slavic languages|Slavic]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Bulgarian historical review|year=2003|publisher=Pub. House of the Bulgarian Academy of Sciences|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lD5pAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Albanian+nobility%22&dq=%22Albanian+nobility%22|accessdate=16 March 2012|page=164|quote=Local principalities... using Greek, Ladin or Slavic as the official languages of correspondence in their courts.}}</ref>\n\n== Restoration ==\nAn attempt to restore the [[monarchy]] in 1997 was rejected by about two-thirds of those voting in a [[Albanian monarchy referendum, 1997|referendum]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/2072440.stm Ex-king's son returns to Albania], ''[[BBC News Online]]'', 28 June 2002.</ref> Former noble families and their descendants are still a part of society in Albania, but they no longer retain any specific privileges.\n\n== Noble families ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Alltuni family]]\n* [[Arianiti family]]\n* [[Bal\u0161i\u0107 noble family|Balshaj family]]\n* [[Blinishti family]]\n* [[:Category:Bua family|Bua]]/[[Shpata family]]\n* [[Bushati family]]\n* [[Dukagjini family]]\n* [[Dushmani family]]\n* [[Gropa family]]\n* [[Humoj family]]\n* [[Jonima family]]\n* [[Losha family]]\n* [[Kastrioti family]]\n* [[K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc family|Qypryli (K\u00f6pr\u00fcl\u00fc) family]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Military history|year=1990|publisher=Empire Press|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ED1WAAAAYAAJ&q=%22Albanian+noblemen%22+-Mozart&dq=%22Albanian+noblemen%22+-Mozart|accessdate=26 March 2012|page=49|quote=The Kuprilis, Albanian noblemen,}}</ref>\n* [[Mataranga family]]\n* [[Muzaka family]]\n* [[Progon family]]\n* [[Shira family]]\n* [[Spani family]]\n* [[Taushani family]]\n* [[Thopia family]]\n* [[Vrioni family]]\n* [[Zaharia family]]\n* [[Zenebishi Family]]\n* [[House of Zogu|Zogu family]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{Citation |author= Serbian Academy of Science |title=Glas, Volumes 319-323|year=1980|publisher=Serbian Academy of Science and Arts|location=Belgrade|url=https://books.google.com/?id=kqorAQAAIAAJ&dq=%D1%85%D1%83%D0%BC%D0%BE%D1%98+%D0%B0%D0%BB%D0%B1%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%98%D0%B0&q=%D1%80%D0%B0%D0%B4%D0%B8%D1%87#search_anchor |language=Serbian|ref=harv}}\n* {{Citation |last=Schmitt |first=Oliver Jens |authorlink=Oliver Jens Schmitt |title=Das venezianische Albanien (1392\u20131479) |url=https://books.google.com/?id=eKKS3u7iPWcC&pg=PA490&dq=%22ben+Koja+hatten%22#v=onepage&q=%22ben%20Koja%20hatten%22&f=false |year=2001 |publisher=R. Oldenbourg Verlag GmbH M\u00fcnchen |location= M\u00fcnchen|isbn=3-486-56569-9 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{Albania topics}}\n{{European nobility}}\n{{Nobility by nation}}\n\n[[Category:Albanian nobility| ]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "link maintenance, refine ref details,Script-assisted fixes: perCS1andMOS:ITALICS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albanian_nobility"}
{"title_page": "Ianina Zanazzi", "text_new": "{{short description|Argentine racecar driver}}\n'''Ianina Zanazzi''' (born January 7, 1982) is an Argentinian professional [[racecar]] driver. She was born in [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]], and started her career in [[karting]] in 1996, moving to [[Hyundai Motor Company|Argentinian Formula Hyundai]] for the 1997 season. In 1998 she competed in both [[Honda|Argentinian Formula Honda]] and [[Formula Renault|Argentinian Formula Renault]]. She moved to the Formula Super Renault for 1999, where she claimed a win at R\u00edo Cuarto, a first for a women in Argentine formula racing.<ref>[https://www.lanacion.com.ar/142932-la-joven-ianina-zanazzi-le-gano-a-todos-en-rio-cuarto La joven Ianina Zanazzi le gan\u00f3 a todos en R\u00edo Cuarto. ''La Naci\u00f3n - 21-06-1999'']</ref> Zanazzi moving to [[Formula Three Sudamericana]] in 2000, in the B-Class. In 2001, she moved to the main class, but only competed in part of the season's schedule. She also competed in a part season of [[Spanish Formula Three]] in 2002.\n\n==Sabotage==\nOn June 1, 2000, Zanazzi was testing her Formula 3 Light car at [[R\u00edo Cuarto, C\u00f3rdoba|R\u00edo Cuarto]] circuit and had a spun off due to an oil spot on the [[asphalt]]. She did not suffer any damage in the incident, but found clues of [[sabotage]] near the zone, and later on it was said that she pointed to team-mate Mariano Bainotti as responsible for such a personal attack on her. However, Zanazzi refused having said that. Bainotti then threatened Zanazzi to sue her for lying, but nothing has happened since.<ref>{{in lang|es}} [http://www.ayudatareas.com.ar/noticias/3/archivo-b3469.shtml Un atentado a las sombras] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531161203/http://www.ayudatareas.com.ar/noticias/3/archivo-b3469.shtml |date=2011-05-31 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.driverdb.com/racingdriver1793.html Driver profile at DriverDB.com]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zanazzi, Ianina}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Buenos Aires]]\n[[Category:Argentine racing drivers]]\n[[Category:Italian Formula Renault 2.0 drivers]]\n[[Category:Formula 3 Sudamericana drivers]]\n[[Category:Euroformula Open Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:Italian female racing drivers]]\n[[Category:Formula Renault Argentina drivers]]\n\n\n{{Argentina-autoracing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Argentine racecar driver}}\n'''Ianina Zanazzi''' (born January 7, 1982 in [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]]) is a professional [[racecar]] driver. She started her career in [[karting]] in 1996, moving to [[Hyundai Motor Company|Argentinian Formula Hyundai]] for the 1997 season. In 1998 she competed in both [[Honda|Argentinian Formula Honda]] and [[Formula Renault|Argentinian Formula Renault]]. She moved to the Formula Super Renault for 1999, where she claimed a win at R\u00edo Cuarto, a first for a women in Argentine formula racing.<ref>[https://www.lanacion.com.ar/142932-la-joven-ianina-zanazzi-le-gano-a-todos-en-rio-cuarto La joven Ianina Zanazzi le gan\u00f3 a todos en R\u00edo Cuarto. ''La Naci\u00f3n - 21-06-1999'']</ref> Zanazzi moving to [[Formula Three Sudamericana]] in 2000, in the B-Class. In 2001, she moved to the main class, but only competed in part of the season's schedule. She also competed in a part season of [[Spanish Formula Three]] in 2002.\n\n==Sabotage==\nOn June 1, 2000, Zanazzi was testing her Formula 3 Light car at [[R\u00edo Cuarto, C\u00f3rdoba|R\u00edo Cuarto]] circuit and had a spun off due to an oil spot on the [[asphalt]]. She did not suffer any damage in the incident, but found clues of [[sabotage]] near the zone, and later on it was said that she pointed to team-mate Mariano Bainotti as responsible for such a personal attack on her. However, Zanazzi refused having said that. Bainotti then threatened Zanazzi to sue her for lying, but nothing has happened since.<ref>{{in lang|es}} [http://www.ayudatareas.com.ar/noticias/3/archivo-b3469.shtml Un atentado a las sombras] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531161203/http://www.ayudatareas.com.ar/noticias/3/archivo-b3469.shtml |date=2011-05-31 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.driverdb.com/racingdriver1793.html Driver profile at DriverDB.com]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zanazzi, Ianina}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Buenos Aires]]\n[[Category:Argentine racing drivers]]\n[[Category:Italian Formula Renault 2.0 drivers]]\n[[Category:Formula 3 Sudamericana drivers]]\n[[Category:Euroformula Open Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:Italian female racing drivers]]\n[[Category:Formula Renault Argentina drivers]]\n\n\n{{Argentina-autoracing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Deb", "label": "safe", "comment": "bring intro into line with bio standards", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ianina_Zanazzi"}
{"title_page": "AppValley", "text_new": "{{Infobox software\n| name = AppValley\n| logo = AppValley.png\n| screenshot = \n| developer = AppValley LLC\n| released = 2019 <!-- {{Start date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| discontinued = \n| latest release version = \n| latest release date = <!-- {{Start date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| programming language = \n| operating system = [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]]\n| platform = \n| size = \n| language = \n| genre = [[App store]]\n| license = \n| website = {{URL|https://app-valley.vip}}\n}}\n'''AppValley''', is an independent American digital distribution service operated by AppValley LLC. It serves as an alternative [[app store]] for the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]] mobile operating system, which allows users to download [[Application software|applications]] that are not available on [[Google Play Store|Google play store]] or [[App Store (iOS)|App store]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digistatement.com/appvalley-apps-not-working-revoked-currently-down-for-many-users/|title=AppValley apps not working & revoked, currently down for many users|date=2020-01-26|website=DigiStatement|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.natureworldnews.com/articles/42878/20191207/how-to-get-tweaked-apps-using-appvalley-on-ios.htm|title=How to Get Tweaked Apps using AppValley on iOS|last=NatureWorldNews|date=2019-12-07|website=Nature World News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe company was founded on March 20, 2019 by Colton Adamski and Logan Sevcik in [[Manhattan, Illinois|Manhattan Illinois]], United States of America. AppValley LLC is an alternative to Apple Appstore where [[Application developer|app developers]] can publish their applications. Colton Adamski is the current chief executive officer at AppValley LLC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencetimes.com/articles/24445/20191210/user-preference-mobile-app-installer-is-now-available-here.htm|title=User Preference Mobile App Installer Is Now Available Here|last=Reporter|first=Staff|date=2019-12-10|website=Science Times|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n== Features ==\nAppValley is a mobile app installer that can be installed and downloaded on the mobile or the devices of the people who wish to get access to many different applications available. AppValley also helps customers to be able to use just one platform to download mobile applications. AppValley also contains apps <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://appvalley.one|title=How to get premium apps using AppValley|website=appvalley.one|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> that have been modified or tweaked for user preferences, and allows the user to by pass national restrictions on the use of apps, without having to resort to [[Jailbreak (computer science)|jailbreaking]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://new.whatmobile.net/Opinion/article/how-can-the-appvalley-help-you-in-getting-access-to-all-the-applications|title=How Can the AppValley Help You in Getting Access to All the Applications|website=new.whatmobile.net|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\nIn 2019, AppValley was along a number of softwares developed that violated enterprise developer certificates to distribute software directly to non-employees, thereby bypassing [[App Store (iOS)|AppStore]]. AppValley's conduct had implications in U.S. sanctioned markets like [[Iran]], Iraq, [[North Korea]], [[Cuba]], and [[Venezuela]], which have all been subject to commercial [[Economic sanctions|sanctions]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.patentlyapple.com/patently-apple/2019/03/apple-suspends-ios-distribution-certificates-of-many-iranian-app-developers.html|title=Apple Suspends iOS Distribution Certificates of many Iranian app Developers|website=Patently Apple|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khmertimeskh.com/50578587/hackers-use-apple-tech-to-put-apps-on-iphones/|title=Hackers use Apple tech to put apps on iPhones|date=2019-02-14|website=Khmer Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> AppValley's initiative helped those countries to have access to [[industrial property]] prohibited to those sanctions. In most of those countries, AppValley served as the only source of sanctioned apps.\n\nThere were allegations that AppValley have also been abusing enterprise developer certificates to distribute apps that offer [[pirated software]], like Instagram, [[Spotify]], [[Pok\u00e9mon Go|Pokemon Go]], and others. For instance, AppValley shares an ad-free version of the music streaming app Spotify even on the free tier.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-apple-piracy-idUSKCN1Q3097|title=Software pirates use Apple tech to put hacked apps on iPhones|date=2019-02-14|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/pirate-developers-using-apple-tech-to-spread-hacked-iphone-apps-11636952|title=Software pirates hijack Apple tech and release rip-off iPhone apps|website=Sky News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/02/14/pirates-load-hacked-paid-apps-on-iphone.html|title=Pirates found a way to load paid apps on iPhones for free, and Apple could be losing money|date=2019-02-14|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Official website|https://app-valley.vip}}\n\n[[Category:Application software]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox software\n| name = AppValley\n| logo = AppValley.png\n| screenshot = \n| developer = AppValley LLC\n| released = 2019 <!-- {{Start date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| discontinued = \n| latest release version = \n| latest release date = <!-- {{Start date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| programming language = \n| operating system = [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]]\n| platform = \n| size = \n| language = \n| genre = [[App store]]\n| license = \n| website = {{URL|https://app-valley.vip}}\n}}\n'''AppValley''', is an independent American digital distribution service operated by AppValley LLC. It serves as an alternative [[app store]] for the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]] mobile operating system, which allows users to download [[Application software|applications]] that are not available on [[Google Play Store|Google play store]] or [[App Store (iOS)|App store]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digistatement.com/appvalley-apps-not-working-revoked-currently-down-for-many-users/|title=AppValley apps not working & revoked, currently down for many users|date=2020-01-26|website=DigiStatement|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.natureworldnews.com/articles/42878/20191207/how-to-get-tweaked-apps-using-appvalley-on-ios.htm|title=How to Get Tweaked Apps using AppValley on iOS|last=NatureWorldNews|date=2019-12-07|website=Nature World News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe company was founded on March 20, 2019 by Colton Adamski and Logan Sevcik in [[Manhattan, Illinois|Manhattan Illinois]], United States of America. AppValley LLC is an alternative to Apple Appstore where [[Application developer|app developers]] can publish their applications. Colton Adamski is the current chief executive officer at AppValley LLC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencetimes.com/articles/24445/20191210/user-preference-mobile-app-installer-is-now-available-here.htm|title=User Preference Mobile App Installer Is Now Available Here|last=Reporter|first=Staff|date=2019-12-10|website=Science Times|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n== Features ==\nAppValley is a mobile app installer that can be installed and downloaded on the mobile or the devices of the people who wish to get access to many different applications available. AppValley also helps customers to be able to use just one platform to download mobile appplications. AppValley also contains apps <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://appvalley.one|title=How to get premium apps using AppValley|website=appvalley.one|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> that have been modified or tweaked for user preferences, and allows the user to by pass national restrictions on the use of apps, without having to resort to [[Jailbreak (computer science)|jailbreaking]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://new.whatmobile.net/Opinion/article/how-can-the-appvalley-help-you-in-getting-access-to-all-the-applications|title=How Can the AppValley Help You in Getting Access to All the Applications|website=new.whatmobile.net|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\nIn 2019, AppValley was along a number of softwares developed that violated enterprise developer certificates to distribute software directly to non-employees, thereby bypassing [[App Store (iOS)|AppStore]]. AppValley's conduct had implications in U.S. sanctioned markets like [[Iran]], Iraq, [[North Korea]], [[Cuba]], and [[Venezuela]], which have all been subject to commercial [[Economic sanctions|sanctions]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.patentlyapple.com/patently-apple/2019/03/apple-suspends-ios-distribution-certificates-of-many-iranian-app-developers.html|title=Apple Suspends iOS Distribution Certificates of many Iranian app Developers|website=Patently Apple|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khmertimeskh.com/50578587/hackers-use-apple-tech-to-put-apps-on-iphones/|title=Hackers use Apple tech to put apps on iPhones|date=2019-02-14|website=Khmer Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> AppValley's initiative helped those countries to have access to [[industrial property]] prohibited to those sanctions. In most of those countries, AppValley served as the only source of sanctioned apps.\n\nThere were allegations that AppValley have also been abusing enterprise developer certificates to distribute apps that offer [[pirated software]], like Instagram, [[Spotify]], [[Pok\u00e9mon Go|Pokemon Go]], and others. For instance, AppValley shares an ad-free version of the music streaming app Spotify even on the free tier.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-apple-piracy-idUSKCN1Q3097|title=Software pirates use Apple tech to put hacked apps on iPhones|date=2019-02-14|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/pirate-developers-using-apple-tech-to-spread-hacked-iphone-apps-11636952|title=Software pirates hijack Apple tech and release rip-off iPhone apps|website=Sky News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/02/14/pirates-load-hacked-paid-apps-on-iphone.html|title=Pirates found a way to load paid apps on iPhones for free, and Apple could be losing money|date=2019-02-14|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Official website|https://app-valley.vip}}\n\n[[Category:Application software]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "appplications->applications -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AppValley"}
{"title_page": "Andrew Cuomo", "text_new": "{{short description|56th Governor of New York}}\n{{pp-semi-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Andrew Cuomo\n| image        = Andrew Cuomo by Pat Arnow cropped.jpeg\n| order        = 56th\n| office       = Governor of New York\n| lieutenant   = [[Robert Duffy (politician)|Robert Duffy]]<br>[[Kathy Hochul]]\n| term_start   = January 1, 2011\n| term_end     =\n| predecessor  = [[David Paterson]]\n| successor    =\n| order2       = 64th\n| office2      = Attorney General of New York\n| governor2    = [[Eliot Spitzer]] <br> [[David Paterson]]\n| term_start2  = January 1, 2007\n| term_end2    = December 31, 2010\n| predecessor2 = [[Eliot Spitzer]]\n| successor2   = [[Eric Schneiderman]]\n| office3      = 11th [[United States Secretary of Housing and Urban Development]]\n| president3   = [[Bill Clinton]]\n| term_start3  = January 29, 1997\n| term_end3    = January 20, 2001\n| predecessor3 = [[Henry Cisneros]]\n| successor3   = [[Mel Mart\u00ednez]]\n| office4      = [[Department of Housing and Urban Development|Assistant Secretary of Housing and Urban Development for Community Planning and Development]]\n| president4   = Bill Clinton\n| term_start4  = May 28, 1993\n| term_end4    = January 29, 1997\n| predecessor4 = Skirma Kondratas\n| successor4   = [[Saul N. Ramirez Jr.|Saul Ramirez, Jr.]]\n| birth_name   = Andrew Mark Cuomo\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1957|12|6}}\n| birth_place  = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Kerry Kennedy]]|1990|2005|end=div}}\n| partner      = [[Sandra Lee (chef)|Sandra Lee]] (2005\u20132019)\n| children     = 3\n| parents      = [[Mario Cuomo]] <br> [[Matilda Cuomo|Matilda Raffa]]\n| relatives    = [[Chris Cuomo]] (brother) <br> [[Margaret Cuomo]] (sister)\n| residence    = [[New York State Executive Mansion|Executive Mansion]]\n| education    = [[Fordham University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]]) <br> [[Albany Law School]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| website      = {{url|governor.ny.gov|Government website}}\n| signature=Andrew_Cuomo_Signature.svg\n}}\n\n'''Andrew Mark Cuomo''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|w|o\u028a|m|o\u028a}} {{respell|KWOH|moh}}; born December 6, 1957) is an American politician, author, and lawyer serving since 2011 as the [[List of Governors of New York|56th]] [[governor of New York]]. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], he was elected to the same position his late father, [[Mario Cuomo]], held for three terms.\n\nBorn in [[New York City]], Cuomo is a graduate of [[Fordham University]] and [[Albany Law School]] of [[Union University (New York)|Union University, New York]]. He began his career working as the campaign manager for his father, then as an assistant district attorney in New York City before entering private law practice. He founded Housing Enterprise for the Less Privileged (HELP USA) and was appointed chair of the New York City Homeless Commission, a position he held from 1990 to 1993.\n\nIn 1993, Cuomo joined the [[Presidency of Bill Clinton|Clinton Administration]] as Assistant Secretary for Community Planning and Development in the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development]]. From 1997 to 2001, he served as the [[United States Secretary of Housing and Urban Development|U.S. Secretary of Housing and Urban Development]].\n\nIn [[2006 New York Attorney General election|2006]], Cuomo was elected [[New York State Attorney General|Attorney General of New York]]. He won the election as [[Governor of New York]] in [[2010 New York gubernatorial election|2010]] and has been reelected twice after winning primaries against liberal challengers [[Zephyr Teachout]] ([[2014 New York gubernatorial election|2014]]) and [[Cynthia Nixon]] ([[2018 New York gubernatorial election|2018]]). During his governorship, Cuomo oversaw the passage of a law legalizing [[Same-sex marriage in New York|same-sex marriage]] in New York; creation of the United States Climate Alliance, a group of states committed to fighting [[climate change]] by following the terms of the Paris Climate Accords; passage of the strictest [[NY SAFE Act|gun control]] law in the U.S.; [[Affordable Care Act|Medicaid expansion]]; a new tax code that raised taxes for the wealthy and lowered taxes for the middle class; paid family leave; an increase in the minimum wage; wage equality; and legislation legalizing medical marijuana.\n{{toclimit|3}}\n\n== Early life and education ==\nCuomo was born in the [[Queens]] borough of [[New York City]],<ref name=\"biography.com\">{{cite web| url = http://www.biography.com/people/andrew-cuomo-21024931 | title=Andrew Cuomo Biography: Government Official, Lawyer (1957\u2013)| publisher= [[Biography.com]] ([[FYI (TV channel)|FYI]] / [[A&E Networks]]) | accessdate= May 25, 2015}}</ref> the elder son of five children born to lawyer and later governor of New York, [[Mario Cuomo]] and [[Matilda Cuomo|Matilda]] (''n\u00e9e'' Raffa).<ref name=\"NYmag021389\">{{cite news|first=Peter|last=Blauner|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=--cCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA35|title=All Star Family Feud: The Governor's In-Laws Battle Over a Father's Legacy|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=February 13, 1989|accessdate=December 6, 2010}}</ref> His parents were both of [[Italian-American|Italian]] descent; his paternal grandparents were from [[Nocera Inferiore]] and [[Tramonti, Campania|Tramonti]] in the [[Campania]] region of southern Italy, while his maternal grandparents were from [[Sicily]] (his grandfather from [[Messina]]).<ref name=\"NYmag021389\" /><ref name=Newsday10201988>{{cite news| first =Michael| last =Arena | author2 =Marianne Arneberg |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/access/104068528.html?dids=104068528:104068528&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+20%2C+1988&author=By+Michael+Arena+and+Marianne+Arneberg&pub=Newsday+(Combined+editions)&desc=Cuomo's+Father-in-Law+Dies&pqatl=google|title=Cuomo's Father-in-Law Dies|work=[[Newsday]]|date=October 20, 1988|accessdate=November 24, 2012}}</ref> His younger brother, [[Chris Cuomo]], is a [[CNN]] journalist. His elder sister is noted radiologist [[Margaret Cuomo]].<ref name=\"NYTimes112310\">{{cite news|first=Michael|last=Barbaro|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/24/nyregion/24sexiest.html|title=All That Time Serving the Public? Very Sexy|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 23, 2010|accessdate=December 6, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101125130807/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/24/nyregion/24sexiest.html| archivedate= November 25, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nHe graduated from St. Gerard Majella's School in 1971<ref>Campanile, Carl. \"[https://nypost.com/2015/05/13/cuomo-and-cardinal-dolan-tout-parochial-school-tax-break/ Cuomo and Cardinal Dolan tout parochial school tax break],\" ''New York Post'', May 13, 2015.</ref> and [[Archbishop Molloy High School]] in 1975.<ref name=\"biography.com\" /> He received a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] from [[Fordham University]] in 1979, and a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] from [[Albany Law School]] in 1982.<ref name=\"biography.com\"/>\n\n== Early career ==\nDuring his father's [[New York gubernatorial election, 1982|1982 campaign for Governor]], Cuomo was campaign manager, and then joined the governor's staff as one of his father's policy advisors and sometime Albany roommate,<ref name=NYm>Smith, Chris. \"[https://nymag.com/news/features/andrew-cuomo-2013-4/ The Albany Machiavelli],\" New York, April 14, 2013.</ref> earning $1 a year.<ref name=\"NYDailyNews092709\">{{cite news |first=Patrice|last=O'Shaughnessy|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/2009/09/27/2009-09-27_andrew_cuomo_from_horror_on_the_hudson_to_democrats_chosen_son.html |title=Andrew Cuomo: From Horror on the Hudson to Democrats' chosen son|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|location=New York |date=September 27, 2009|accessdate=December 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1984 to 1985, Cuomo was a New York assistant district attorney, and briefly worked at the law firm of Blutrich, Falcone & Miller. He founded Housing Enterprise for the Less Privileged (HELP) in 1986 and left his law firm to run HELP full-time in 1988.<ref name=\"NYDailyNews092709\" /> From 1990 to 1993, during the administration of [[Mayor of New York City|New York City mayor]], [[David Dinkins]], Cuomo was chair of the New York City Homeless Commission, which was charged with developing policies to address the homeless issue in the city and developing more housing options.{{cn|date=August 2019}}\n\n== Secretary of HUD ==\n[[File:HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Cuomo as HUD Secretary]]\nAndrew Cuomo was appointed to the [[Department of Housing and Urban Development]] as Assistant Secretary for Community Planning and Development in 1993, a member of President [[Bill Clinton]]'s administration.<ref name=\"HUD\" /> After the departure of Secretary [[Henry Cisneros]] at the end of Clinton's first term under the cloud of an FBI investigation,<ref name=\"evans\">{{cite news | last =Evans | first =Judith | title =HUD's Cisneros to Leave a Legacy of Public Housing Reform | work =[[The Washington Post]] | page =E01 | date =November 30, 1996 | url =https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/cisneros/stories/cis113096.htm | accessdate =January 12, 2011 }}</ref> Cuomo was unanimously confirmed by the [[United States Senate]] to succeed him as [[Secretary of HUD]]. Cuomo served as Secretary from January 1997 until the Clinton administration ended in 2001.<ref name=\"HUD\" />\n\nIn 2000, Cuomo led HUD efforts to negotiate an agreement with the United States' largest handgun manufacturer, [[Smith & Wesson]], that required Smith & Wesson to change the design, distribution and marketing of guns to make them safer and to help keep them out of the hands of children and criminals.<ref name=\"HUD\">{{cite web|url=http://archives.hud.gov/secretaries/cuomobio.cfm |title=Andrew M. Cuomo |publisher=Archives, U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development |accessdate=May 20, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100527090837/http://archives.hud.gov/secretaries/cuomobio.cfm| archivedate= May 27, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Budgets enacted during his term contained initiatives to increase the supply of affordable housing and home ownership, and to create jobs and economic development. These included new rental assistance subsidies, reforms to integrate public housing, higher limits on mortgages insured by the [[Federal Housing Administration]], a crackdown on housing discrimination, expanded programs to help homeless people get housing and jobs, and creation of new [[Empowerment Zone|empowerment zone]]s.\n\n[[File:CuomoSummers.jpg|thumb|upright|Cuomo as HUD Secretary holding a press conference with then Treasury Secretary [[Larry Summers]]]]\nDuring Cuomo's tenure as HUD Secretary, he called for an increase in home ownership.<ref name=\"Fairbanks\">{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/city/article50994.ece |title=Cuomo's HUD career under scrutiny |work=[[The Buffalo News]] |date=August 21, 2010|accessdate=September 17, 2010|first=Phil|last=Fairbanks| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100825154017/http://www.buffalonews.com/city/article50994.ece| archivedate= August 25, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> He also pushed government-sponsored lenders [[Fannie Mae]] and [[Freddie Mac]] to buy more home loans issued to poor homeowners, in an attempt to end discrimination against minorities.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/24/nyregion/24hud.html |title=As HUD Chief, Cuomo Earns a Mixed Score |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 23, 2010 |author1=David M. Halbfinger |author2=Michael Powell |accessdate=September 17, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140127034455/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/24/nyregion/24hud.html |archivedate=January 27, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some believe that this helped lead to the recent [[subprime mortgage crisis]].<ref name=\"Fairbanks\" /><ref name=\"Barrett\">{{cite web|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2008-08-05/news/how-andrew-cuomo-gave-birth-to-the-crisis-at-fannie-mae-and-freddie-mac/ |title=Andrew Cuomo and Fannie and Freddie |work=[[The Village Voice]] |date=August 5, 2008 |accessdate=September 17, 2010 |first=Wayne |last=Barrett |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722145449/http://www.villagevoice.com/2008-08-05/news/how-andrew-cuomo-gave-birth-to-the-crisis-at-fannie-mae-and-freddie-mac/ |archivedate=July 22, 2010 }}</ref> Edward J. Pinto, former chief credit officer at Fannie Mae, said \"they should have known the risks were large. Cuomo was pushing mortgage bankers to make loans and basically saying you have to offer a loan to everybody.\"<ref name=\"Fairbanks\" /> But others disagree with the assessment that Cuomo caused the crisis. [[Dean Baker]], co-director of the [[Center for Economic and Policy Research]], said Cuomo \"was a contributor in terms of him being a cheerleader, but I don't think we can pin too much blame on him.\"<ref name=\"Fairbanks\" />\n\nAccording to libertarian author and critic [[James Bovard]], Cuomo was obsessed with changing HUD's image, as Cuomo declared, \"The PR is the important thing I do ... Eighty percent of the battle is communications.\" He championed a new program called Community Builders, created without appropriation by Congress, for 800 new HUD employees with computers to be paid as much as $100,000. In a June 16, 1999, speech, Cuomo declared that one purpose of the program was to fight against HUD's abolition. In August 1999, Community Builders distributed a letter to community groups to fight against proposed tax cuts. One HUD official declared that Community Builders were seen as \"Democratic [[ward heeler]]s who act as a pipeline between Democratic city officials, party leaders, and the administration and the [[Democratic National Committee]].\"\n\nIn 1998, Clinton-appointed HUD inspector general Susan Gaffney testified to a Senate committee that she was the victim of \"'escalating' attacks on her office by Cuomo and 'his key aides,' including cooked-up charges of racism, insubordination, malfeasance, and general dirty-dealing.\" In 1999, Gaffney's office concluded that \"most (15 out of 19) Community Builders' goals were activities rather than actual accomplishments.\" and that Cuomo's initiatives \"had a crippling effect on many of HUD's ongoing operations.\"<ref>{{cite book | first=James | last=Bovard | authorlink=James Bovard | year= 2000 | title= Feeling Your Pain: The Explosion and Abuse Of Government Power in the Clinton-Gore Years | publisher= St. Martin's Press | location= New York | id=0-312-23082-6 | pages= 182\u2013184}}</ref>  Gaffney retired in May 2001, shortly after the department reached a $490,000 settlement with a black employee who had accused her of racial discrimination in passing him over for a promotion.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nakashima |first=Ellen |agency=''[[Washington Post]]'' |date=May 6, 2001 |title=HUD's Inspector General Retiring After Racial-Bias Suit Settlement |url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-2001-05-06-0105060155-story.html |work=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |location=Deerfield Beach, FL}}</ref>\n\nPrior to Cuomo's tenure, HUD was routinely included on the General Accounting Office's biannual watch list of government programs whose poor management made them prone to fraud.<ref name=\"Making\">{{cite news |last=Mahler |first=Jonathan |date=August 11, 2010 |title=The Making of Andrew Cuomo |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/15/magazine/15Cuomo-t.html |work=[[The New York Times Magazine]] |location=New York, NY |url-access=subscription |page=30}}</ref> During his time in office, two of HUD's four main departments were removed from the GAO list.<ref name=\"Making\"/> In addition, the department cut 15 percent of its staff as part of a Cuomo initiative to streamline its operations.<ref name=\"Making\"/>\n\n== 2002 New York gubernatorial election ==\n{{see also|2002 New York gubernatorial election}}\nCuomo first ran for the Democratic nomination for Governor of New York in 2002. He was initially the favorite for nomination and led in fund-raising and polls, but his campaign took serious damage after a [[gaffe]] when Cuomo said (in reference to the aftermath of the [[September 11 attacks]]) \"[[George Pataki|Pataki]] stood behind the leader. He held the leader's coat. He was a great assistant to the leader. But he was not a leader. Cream rises to the top, and [[Rudy Giuliani]] rose to the top.\" His remarks were widely derided; even his father, former governor [[Mario Cuomo]], later admitted it was a blunder.<ref name=\"Dreher\">{{cite news|first=Rod|last=Dreher |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/dreher/dreher090402.asp|title=Where the Son Doesn't Follow|work=[[National Review]]|date=September 4, 2002|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020910104631/http://www.nationalreview.com/dreher/dreher090402.asp|archivedate=September 10, 2002}}</ref>\n\nOn the eve of the state convention, Cuomo withdrew from consideration after concluding that he had little chance of support as opposed to the favored party candidate, [[New York State Comptroller|State Comptroller]] [[Carl McCall]].<ref name=\"Schneider\">{{cite news| first=Bill| last=Schneider| url=http://archives.cnn.com/2002/ALLPOLITICS/09/06/ip.pol.umbrella/index.html|title=Let a political connection be your umbrella?|work=Inside Politics|publisher=CNN|date=September 6, 2002|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050319094326/http://archives.cnn.com/2002/ALLPOLITICS/09/06/ip.pol.umbrella/index.html|archivedate=March 19, 2005}}</ref> McCall went on to lose the general election to [[George Pataki]].\n\n== New York attorney general ==\n=== Election ===\n{{main|2006 New York Attorney General election}}\nCuomo declared his candidacy for the Democratic nomination for [[New York State Attorney General|New York State attorney general]] in 2006, and on May 30, 2006, captured the Democratic Party's endorsement, receiving 65% of the delegates. Though Cuomo won the endorsement, former [[New York City Public Advocate|New York City public advocate]] [[Mark J. Green]] and two-time candidate for [[Lieutenant Governor of New York|Lieutenant Governor]] [[Charlie King (politician)|Charlie King]], also earned places on the Democratic [[primary election|ballot]].<ref name=\"Hicks\">{{cite news|first=Jonathan P.|last=Hicks|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/05/31/nyregion/31ag.html|title=Cuomo Wins Democrats' Backing in Primary Race for Attorney General|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 31, 2006|accessdate=July 23, 2007}}</ref> King dropped out of the race before the primary and endorsed Cuomo.<ref name=\"NYDailyNews022610\">{{cite news|first=Elizabeth|last=Benjamin|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/2010/02/sharpton-praises-paterson-wont.html|title=Sharpton Praises Paterson, Won't Endorse Cuomo Today | location=New York |work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|date=February 26, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100303002407/http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/2010/02/sharpton-praises-paterson-wont.html|archivedate=March 3, 2010}}</ref>\n\nCuomo won the primary with a majority of the vote, defeating his nearest opponent by over 20%. Clinching the Democratic party nomination was considered a significant rebound following his unsuccessful and unpopular 2002 gubernatorial campaign and at the nominating convention, June O'Neill, the Democratic chairwoman of [[St. Lawrence County]], called him \"New York's own Comeback Kid.\"<ref name=\"Hicks\" /> He won the [[general election]] against the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee, former [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester]] [[District attorney]] [[Jeanine Pirro]] on November 7, 2006, winning 58% of the vote.\n\n=== Tenure ===\n==== Police surveillance, 2007 ====\n{{main|Eliot Spitzer political surveillance controversy}}\nOn July 23, 2007, Cuomo's office admonished the [[Eliot Spitzer|Spitzer administration]] for ordering the State Police to keep special records of then-Senate majority leader [[Joseph Bruno]]'s whereabouts when he traveled with police escorts in New York City.<ref name=\"nyt072307\">{{cite news|first=Danny|last=Hakim|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/23/nyregion/23cnd-spitzer.html|title=Spitzer's Staff Misused Police, Report Finds|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 23, 2007|accessdate=July 24, 2007}}</ref> At the discretion of top officials of the Spitzer administration, the [[New York State Police]] created documents meant to cause political damage to Bruno.<ref name=\"ijour072307\">{{cite news|first=Cara |last=Matthews |url=http://www.theithacajournal.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070723/NEWS01/70723006/1002 |title=Cuomo: Spitzer aides used state police to try to damage Bruno |work=[[The Ithaca Journal]] |date=July 23, 2007 |accessdate=July 24, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://m.lohud.com/detail.jsp?key=62289&full=1 |archivedate=March 17, 2008 }}</ref> Spitzer responded by accepting responsibility and issuing an apology to Bruno.<ref name=\"nyt072307\" /><ref name=\"siadv\">{{cite news |first=Sally |last=Goldenberg |url=http://blog.silive.com/advanceupdate/2007/07/report_governor_office_compil.html|title=Report: Governor's office compiled, leaked data on Bruno |work=[[Staten Island Advance]] |date=July 23, 2007 |accessdate=July 24, 2007}}{{dead link|date=February 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== Student loan inquiry, 2007 ====\nIn 2007, Cuomo was active in a high-profile investigation into lending practices and anti-competitive relationships between student lenders and universities. Specifically, many universities steered student borrowers to a \"preferred lender,\" which resulted in the borrowers' incurring higher interest rates. This led to changes in lending policy at many major American universities. Many universities also rebated millions of dollars in fees back to affected borrowers.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/money/industries/banking/2007-04-10-cuomo-student-loan-probe_N.htm |title=Cuomo: School loan corruption widespread|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=April 8, 2008| date=April 10, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Doug|last=Lederman|url=http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2007/05/15/texas|title=The First Casualty|publisher=Inside Higher Education|date=May 15, 2007|accessdate=April 8, 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[File:CuomoAckerman.jpg|thumb|240px|Cuomo with Representative [[Gary Ackerman]]]]\n\n==== Usenet, 2008 ====\nOn June 10, 2008, Cuomo announced that three major Internet service providers ([[Verizon Communications]], [[Time Warner Cable]], and [[Sprint Nextel|Sprint]]) would \"shut down major sources of online [[child pornography]]\" by no longer hosting many [[Usenet]] groups. Time Warner Cable ceased offering Usenet altogether, Sprint ended access to the 18,408 newsgroups in the [[alt.* hierarchy]], and Verizon limited its Usenet offerings to the approximately 3,000 [[Big 8 (Usenet)|Big 8]] newsgroups. The move came after Cuomo's office located 88 different newsgroups to which child pornography had been posted.<ref>Rosencrance, Lisa. \"[http://www.computerworld.com/action/article.do?command=viewArticleBasic&articleId=9095778 3 top ISPs to block access to sources of child porn].\" ''[[Computer World]]''. June 8, 2008. Retrieved September 23, 2010.</ref><ref name=\"DeJeanNotDeadYet2\">DeJean, David. \"Usenet: Not Dead Yet.\" ''[[PC World (magazine)|PC World]]''. Tuesday October 7, 2008. [https://www.pcworld.com/article/151989-2/usenet_not_dead_yet.html 2]. Retrieved September 23, 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=McCullagh | first= Declan | title= N.Y. attorney general forces ISPs to curb Usenet access | url= http://news.cnet.com/8301-13578_3-9964895-38.html | date= June 10, 2008 | publisher=CNET News | accessdate=April 28, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==== 2008 Obama remarks ====\nIn 2008, Cuomo said of the Democratic Party candidate [[Barack Obama]], who was running against [[Hillary Clinton]], the candidate Cuomo supported: \"You can't shuck and jive at a press conference.\" Cuomo received criticism from some for his use of the phrase. [[Roland S. Martin|Roland Martin]] of [[CNN]] said that \"'[[shuckin' and jivin']]' have long been words used as a negative assessment of African Americans, along the lines of a 'foot-shufflin' [[Negro]].'\"<ref>[http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2008/01/11/martin-shucking-and-jiving-and-the-campaign-trail/ \"Martin: 'Shucking and jiving' and the campaign trail\"], CNN Political Ticker \u2013 CNN.com Blogs, January 11, 2008.</ref>\n\n==== Corruption and fraud investigations, 2009 ====\nCuomo investigated a corruption scandal, \"fraudulent scheme to extract kickbacks\", which involved New York investigators, the [[Securities and Exchange Commission]], and [[state attorney general|attorneys general]] in dozens of states.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/15/business/15leuschen.html Go-Between Tied Funds to Carlyle]. New York Times, May 14, 2009</ref>\n\nAlso in 2009, Cuomo launched a suit against the [[United Homeless Organization]], a New York charity. He charged that the majority of the group's income was not used to provide services to the homeless, but was diverted to the founders for unrelated personal expenses.<ref name=\"nyp_20091123\">{{citation | title=Homeless beggar jars a sham: AG | publisher=[[New York Post]] | date=2009-11-24 | url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/local/suit_put_cork_in_it_jugheads_GvF3qaHCib8Xh5AY86i68O?offset=16#comments#ixzz0Xmpl4OA1 | accessdate=2009-11-24 | first1=Melissa | last1=Klein | first2=Kevin | last2=Fasick | first3=Chuck | last3=Bennett}}</ref> In 2010, Judge [[Barbara R. Kapnick]] granted the judgement and forced the group to disband.<ref name=\"UHO Shut Down\">{{cite news| url= http://www.nypost.com/p/news/local/judge_rules_hucksters_permanently_ahPPxEVrVEHlimCcLjlQ4I| title=Judge rules to permanently shut down faux homeless charity, but hucksters still out in force|last=Bennett|first=Chuck|date=|work=New York Post|access-date=|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Potential U.S. Senate appointment ==\n{{See also|United States Senate special election in New York, 2010#Potential candidates|l1=Possible appointment choices for the New York Senate seat}}\nAfter [[Hillary Clinton]] became President Obama's choice for [[U.S. Secretary of State|U.S. secretary of state]], then-New York governor [[David Paterson]] was charged with appointing a temporary replacement until a [[United States Senate special election in New York, 2010|special election]]. Cuomo was seen as a leading contender for this appointment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/22/us/politics/22hillary.html|title=If Clinton Should Win, Who Would Take Her Place?|accessdate=November 23, 2008|date=January 22, 2007|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=Chan, Sewell |author2= Richard P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a}}</ref><ref name=WaHfCS /> [[Caroline Kennedy]] (also the first cousin of Cuomo's ex-wife) was another leading contender, but withdrew for personal reasons two days before Paterson was set to announce his choice, leaving Cuomo and U.S. representative [[Kirsten Gillibrand]] as the most likely appointees.<ref name=WaHfCS>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/04/us/politics/04senateseat.html|title=Wishing and Hoping for Clinton's Seat|accessdate=November 23, 2008|date=October 4, 2007|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=Hakim, Danny}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/22/nyregion/22york.html|title=New York Weighs Options to Fill the Seat of Senator Clinton |accessdate=November 23, 2008|date=November 21, 2008|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=Hakim, Danny| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081210011131/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/22/nyregion/22york.html| archivedate= December 10, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> On January 23, Paterson announced he would appoint Gillibrand to the U.S. Senate.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/01/23/gillibrand.profile/index.html | title=N.Y. governor names Clinton successor | author=Silverleib, Alan |publisher=CNN | date=January 23, 2009 | accessdate=January 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Governor of New York ==\n=== Elections ===\n==== 2010 ====\n{{main|2010 New York gubernatorial election}}\nOn September 18, 2009, advisors to President Barack Obama informed Governor [[David Paterson]] that the president believed he should withdraw his 2010 gubernatorial candidacy, stepping aside for \"popular Attorney General Andrew Cuomo.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/news/region-state/obama-cordial-but-cool-to-gov-paterson-1.1465587 |title=Obama cordial but cool to Gov. David Paterson |work=Newsday |date=September 21, 2009 |accessdate=May 16, 2010}}</ref> On January 23, 2010, the New York ''Daily News'' reported that Cuomo would announce plans for a gubernatorial campaign at the end of March.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/2010/01/23/2010-01-23_source_says_andrew_cuomo_will_announce_plans_to_run_for_new_york_governor_in_mar.html| title=Source says Andrew Cuomo will announce plans to run for New York Governor in March|date=January 23, 2010|accessdate=January 24, 2010|author=Molloy, Joanna|newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]| location=New York | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100127181447/http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/2010/01/23/2010-01-23_source_says_andrew_cuomo_will_announce_plans_to_run_for_new_york_governor_in_mar.html| archivedate= January 27, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Later reports indicated Cuomo would announce his gubernatorial campaign coinciding with the state Democratic Convention in late May.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=ao6UppVoMprA |title=Cuomo Said to Wait for N.Y. Convention to Declare Governor Run |publisher=Bloomberg |date=May 30, 2005 |accessdate=May 16, 2010 |first=Henry |last=Goldman}}</ref> On May 22, 2010, Cuomo announced his run for governor in a video posted to his campaign website. Cuomo announced his choice for lieutenant governor on May 26, 2010: Mayor of [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]], [[Robert Duffy (politician)|Robert Duffy]].<ref name=\"DuffySelection\">{{cite news|url=http://rochester.ynn.com/content/top_stories/505988/cuomo-names-mayor-duffy-as-running-mate/|title=Cuomo Names Mayor Duffy as Running Mate|work=Your News Now (YNN) Rochester|date=May 26, 2010|accessdate=February 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the November 2, 2010, general election, Cuomo faced Republican [[Carl Paladino]], a [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]]-based businessman who had been heavily supported by the [[Tea Party movement]]. Cuomo won the election for governor by a landslide, winning 62.6% of the vote. Paladino performed strongly in his native Buffalo area, while Cuomo performed well in the eastern part of the state as well as downstate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/city/article187686.ece|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208193115/http://www.buffalonews.com/city/article187686.ece|url-status=dead|title=\"Long Islanders put Paladino to test as their cup of tea,\" ''Buffalo News'', September 12, 2010.|archivedate=February 8, 2012}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n[[File:NYGov10County.png|thumb|Election results by county]]\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9\"\n! colspan=\"7\" | New York gubernatorial general election results, 2010 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2010/general/2010GovernorRecertified09122012.pdf |title=NYS Board of Elections Governor/Lt. Governor Election Returns November 2, 2010 |accessdate=2013-12-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105210422/http://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2010/general/2010GovernorRecertified09122012.pdf |archivedate=November 5, 2013 }}</ref>\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 15em\" |Party\n! style=\"width: 10em\" |Candidate\n! style=\"width: 10em\" |Running mate\n! style=\"width: 5em\" |Votes\n! style=\"width: 7em\" |Percentage\n! style=\"width: 5em\" |Swing\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#3333FF; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Andrew Cuomo''\n| align=\"right\" | 2,609,465\n| align=\"right\" | 56.52%\n| align=\"right\" | {{decrease}} 1.82%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#CC6699; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Working Families Party|Working Families]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Andrew Cuomo''\n| align=\"right\" | 154,835\n| align=\"right\" | 3.35%\n| align=\"right\" | {{increase}} 0.05%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#800080; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Independence Party of New York|Independence]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Andrew Cuomo''\n| align=\"right\" | 146,576\n| align=\"right\" | 3.17%\n| align=\"right\" | {{decrease}} 0.89%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#B2BEB5; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | Total\n| '''Andrew Cuomo'''\n| '''[[Robert Duffy (politician)|Robert Duffy]]'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''2,910,876'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''63.05%'''\n| align=\"right\" | {{decrease}} 2.65%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FF3333; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Carl Paladino''\n| align=\"right\" | 1,289,817\n| align=\"right\" | 27.94%\n| align=\"right\" | {{increase}} 4.40%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FF8C00; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Conservative Party of New York State|Conservative]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Carl Paladino''\n| align=\"right\" | 232,215\n| align=\"right\" | 5.03%\n| align=\"right\" | {{increase}} 1.44%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#006A4E; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Taxpayers Party of New York|Taxpayers]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Carl Paladino''\n| align=\"right\" | 25,825\n| align=\"right\" | 0.56%\n| align=\"right\" |\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#B2BEB5; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | Total\n| [[Carl Paladino]]\n| Greg Edwards\n| align=\"right\" | 1,547,857\n| align=\"right\" | 33.53%\n| align=\"right\" | {{increase}} 6.41%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#0BDA51; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Green Party of the United States|Green]]\n| [[Howie Hawkins]]\n| Gloria Mattera\n| align=\"right\" | 59,906\n| align=\"right\" | 1.30%\n| align=\"right\" | {{increase}} 0.41%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FFD700; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]]\n| [[Warren Redlich]]\n| Alden Link\n| align=\"right\" | 48,359\n| align=\"right\" | 1.05%\n| align=\"right\" | {{increase}} 0.74%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#703642; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Rent Is Too Damn High Party|Rent Is Too Damn High]]\n| [[Jimmy McMillan]]\n| None\n| align=\"right\" | 41,129\n| align=\"right\" | 0.89%\n| align=\"right\" | {{increase}} 0.61%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#C9FFE5; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Freedom Party of New York (2010)|Freedom]]\n| [[Charles Barron]]\n| Eva M. Doyle\n| align=\"right\" | 24,571\n| align=\"right\" | 0.53%\n| align=\"right\" |\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#B5A642; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | Anti-Prohibition\n| [[Kristin M. Davis]]\n| Tanya Gendelman\n| align=\"right\" | 20,421\n| align=\"right\" | 0.44%\n| align=\"right\" |\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#B2BEB5; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" | '' Scattering''\n| align=\"right\" | 4,836\n| align=\"right\" | 0.10%\n| align=\"right\" | N/A\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"right\"| '''Majority'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''1,363,019'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''29.52%'''\n| align=\"right\" | {{decrease}} 9.06%\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n| colspan=\"4\" align=\"right\" | '''Totals'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''4,616,836'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''100.00%'''\n| align=\"right\" |\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#3333FF; width: 3px\" |\n| colspan=\"6\" | '''[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] Hold'''\n|}\n\nIn addition to the parties fielding candidates, New York's [[electoral fusion]] laws allow parties to cross-endorse candidates. The [[Independence Party of New York|Independence Party]] and [[Working Families Party of New York|Working Families Party]] cross-endorsed Andrew Cuomo, while the [[Conservative Party of New York|Conservative Party]] and [[Taxpayers Party of New York|Taxpayers Party]] cross-endorsed Carl Paladino. The Independence Party line received 146,648 votes (5.0% of Cuomo's total, and 3.2% of the statewide total) and the Working Families line received 154,853 votes (5.3% and 3.4%), with the Democratic line receiving the remaining 2,610,220 votes (89.6% and 56.5%). The Conservative line received 232,281 votes (15.0% of Paladino's total, and 5.0% of the statewide total) and the Taxpayers line received 25,821 votes (1.5% and 0.6%), with the Republican line receiving the remaining 1,290,082 votes (83.3% and 27.1%).\n\n==== 2014 ====\n{{see also|2014 New York gubernatorial election}}\nCuomo sought reelection in 2014, with former U.S. Representative Kathy Hochul as his new running mate. On March 5, 2014, [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester]] [[County Executive|County executive]] [[Rob Astorino]] announced that he would run on the Republican ticket against Cuomo for governor.<ref name=\"Astorino\">{{cite news|last=McKinley |first=Jesse | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/06/nyregion/astorino-bid-for-new-york-governor.html|title=Westchester Leader Opens Bid to Deny Cuomo a Second Term|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 5, 2014|accessdate=March 26, 2014}}</ref> Law professors [[Zephyr Teachout]] and [[Tim Wu]] challenged the Cuomo\u2013Hochul ticket in the Democratic primary election<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.firedoglake.com/2014/09/10/cuomo-spent-nearly-40-times-more-than-teachout-to-win-primary/|title=Cuomo Spent Nearly 40 Times More Than Teachout To Win Primary|work=Shadowproof}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wnyc.org/story/election-night-stub/|title=Cuomo Wins Democratic Primary|publisher=WNYC}}</ref>\u2014capturing 34% of the vote on the gubernatorial line (Wu drew 40.1% as lieutenant governor<ref>{{cite web|url=http://project.wnyc.org/election2014-ny-state/|title=Election Results \u2013 2014 NY State Primary \u2013 WNYC|author=WNYC Data News|publisher=wnyc.org}}</ref>).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/zephyr-teachout-primary-loss-air-victory-party-article-1.1934371|title=Zephyr Teachout's primary election loss has air of a victory party, Annie Karni, NYTimes, 10 Sept. 2014|work=Daily News|location=New York}}</ref> On November 4, 2014, Cuomo was re-elected for a second term with 54% of the vote,<ref name=Kaplan141104>{{cite news |last=Kaplan |first=Thomas |date=November 4, 2014 |title=Andrew Cuomo Is Re-elected New York Governor, but Loses Clout |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/05/nyregion/andrew-cuomo-is-re-elected-governor-of-new-york.html |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=January 15, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/Election-Day-2014-New-York-Governor-Andrew-Cuomo-Rob-Astorino-Vote-281478431.html|title=Andrew Cuomo Wins Re-election in NY Governor's Race|work=NBC New York}}</ref> while Astorino received 40.6% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://project.wnyc.org/election2014/|title=Election 2014 \u2013 WNYC|author=WNYC Data News|publisher=wnyc.org}}</ref>\n\n